{"title_page": "Battle of Tudela", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Tudela\n|partof=the [[Peninsular War]]\n|image=La batalla de Tudela, por January Suchodolski.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=''Battle of Tudela'', 1827, [[January Suchodolski]], [[National Museum in Warsaw]]\n|date=23 November 1808\n|place=[[Tudela, Navarre|Tudela]], [[Kingdom of Navarre|Navarre]], [[Enlightenment in Spain|Spain]]\n|result=Franco-Polish victory\n|combatant1={{flagdeco|First French Empire}} [[First French Empire|France]] <br> {{flagdeco|Poland}} [[Duchy of Warsaw]]\n|combatant2={{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Enlightenment in Spain|Spain]]\n|commander1={{flagdeco|First French Empire}} [[Jean Lannes]] <br> {{flagdeco|First French Empire}} [[Michel Ney]] <br> {{flagdeco|First French Empire}} [[Charles Lefebvre-Desnouettes|Lefebvre-Desnouettes]]\n|commander2={{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Francisco Javier Casta\u00f1os, 1st Duke of Bail\u00e9n|Duke of Bail\u00e9n]]<br>{{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Jos\u00e9 Rebolledo de Palafox, 1st Duke of Saragossa|Duke of Saragossa]]<br>{{flagdeco|Spain|1785}} [[Juan O'Neylle]]\n|strength1=31,000 \n|strength2=33,000\n|casualties1=650 killed or wounded\n|casualties2=4,000 killed, wounded, or captured\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Peninsular War (1808-1809)}}\n{{Campaignbox Peninsular War}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Tudela''' (23 November 1808) saw an [[First French Empire|Imperial French]] army led by [[Marshal of France|Marshal]] [[Jean Lannes]] attack a [[Kingdom of Spain|Spanish]] army under [[Francisco Javier Casta\u00f1os, 1st Duke of Bail\u00e9n|General Casta\u00f1os]]. The battle resulted in the complete victory of the Imperial forces over their adversaries. The combat occurred near [[Tudela, Navarre|Tudela in Navarre]], [[Spain]] during the [[Peninsular War]], part of a wider conflict known as the [[Napoleonic Wars]].\n\nSpanish casualties were estimated to be about 4,000 dead and 3,000 prisoners out of a total force of 33,000. The French and Poles lost no more than 650 dead and wounded out of a total of 31,000. This is one of the battles whose name was engraved on the [[Arc de Triomphe]] in [[Paris]].<ref>[http://arcdetriomphe.info/battles/tudela/ Arc de Triomphe website]</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Dos de Mayo Uprising]] of 2 May 1808, followed by extensive uprisings throughout Spain, forced the French to pull back from their occupation of Spain to the [[Ebro]] River. There was an opportunity for the Spanish to finally expel the French altogether but this was missed due to their failure to appoint a Supreme Commander leaving the individual Spanish forces to operate independently.\n\nThese Spanish forces consisted of the army of General [[Joaqu\u00edn Blake]] on the North coast, the army of General [[Francisco Javier Casta\u00f1os, 1st Duke of Bail\u00e9n|Francisco Javier Casta\u00f1os]] around [[Tudela, Navarre|Tudela]] and the army of General [[Jos\u00e9 Rebolledo de Palafox, 1st Duke of Saragossa|Jos\u00e9 Rebolledo de Palafox]] around [[Zaragoza]]. Blake was active in attacking the French but his offensive near [[Bilbao]] was defeated at [[Battle of Pancorbo (1808)|Pancorbo]] on 31 October 1808.\n\n[[Napoleon]]\u2019s strategy was to make a strong attack towards [[Burgos]] splitting off the army of Blake from the others and to outflank them by then swinging both north and south. It was in his interest that the Spanish maintain their exposed advanced positions. The French armies facing them were therefore ordered not to attack. So from October to 21 November 1808, Marshal [[Bon-Adrien Jeannot de Moncey]]\u2019s [[III Corps (Grande Arm\u00e9e)|III Corps]] remained static in front of Casta\u00f1os's army.\n\nThe Spanish armies were however in a constant state of movement to no effect. For much of the time Casta\u00f1os was ill leaving Palafox to direct operations. Palafox seems to have been indecisive on what course of action to take.<ref>This section is based on Rickard, J (28 February 2008), Battle of Tudela, 23 November 1808 [http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_tudela.html ]</ref>\n\n==Battlefield==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=September 2014}}\nThe battlefield was the area between Tudela and the neighbouring hills on the left. The Spanish front was deployed on the hills of Santa Barbara, Tudela, Torre Monreal, Santa Quiteria the top of Cabezoe Maya (the hill where the retreat of San Juan de Calchetas was), and the villages of Urzante (now disappeared), [[Murchante]], and [[Cascante]]. Separating the Spanish and the French was the [[Queiles]] River, a tributary of the [[Ebro]].\n\nThe French advanced from the Cierzo hills that were in front of the Spanish lines towards the Spanish troops.\n\n==Preliminaries==\nOn 21 November 1808 Casta\u00f1os was around [[Calahorra]] on the Ebro between [[Logrono]] and Tudela. On this day the French III Corps crossed the Ebro at Logrono and headed east towards Calahorra while at the same time Marshal [[Michel Ney]] with the [[VI Corps (Grande Arm\u00e9e)|VI Corps]] reached the Upper [[Douro]] Valley and headed towards Tudela.\n\n[[File:Esquema posiciones224.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.6|Diagram of Spanish positions: Santa Barbara - La Pe\u00f1a Division]]\n\nThese movements threatened Casta\u00f1os with entrapment between these two armies. To avoid this Casta\u00f1os withdrew to Tudela. He decided to defend a line {{convert|17|km|mi|0}} long stretching west from Tudela along the Ebro, then along the [[Queiles]] River to [[Cascante]] and finally to [[Tarazona]] at the foot of the [[Moncayo Massif]].\n\nCasta\u00f1os had insufficient men to hold a line of this length so he asked General [[Juan O'Neylle]], who had two divisions at [[Caparroso]] on the east bank of the Ebro, for help. As O\u2019Neylle was under the command of Palafox he refused to move without an order from Palafox. This did not arrive until noon on 22 November 1808. O\u2019Neylle moved promptly to the east bank of the Ebro opposite Tudela but decided not to cross the river until the next day.\n\nBy nightfall on 22 November 1808 Casta\u00f1os had almost 45,000 soldiers in the vicinity of Tudela but very few of them actually in position. Casta\u00f1os placed General [[Manuel la Pe\u00f1a]]\u2019s 4th Division of 8,000 men, mostly [[Andalusian people|Andalusians]] who had participated in the [[Battle of Bail\u00e9n]], at [[Cascante]] and General Grimarest at the head of three divisions totaling 13,000 to 14,000 soldiers at Tarazona. General Roca's division was on the east bank of the Ebro plus the two divisions from Aragon of O\u2019Neylle and [[Felipe Augusto de Saint-Marcq]].<ref>[http://www.aulamilitar.com/pagiht17.htm El regimiento de voluntarios de Segorbe (1808\u20131809) [[File:Flag of Spain (1785-1873 and 1875-1931).svg|20px]](Es)]</ref>\n\nMost of the fighting in the battle of Tudela would involve only the three divisions of Roca, O\u2019Neylle, and Saint-Marcq \u2013 totaling about 23,000 infantry.\n\nFor the French only the III Corps was involved in the Battle of Tudela. Prior to 22 November 1808 this force had been commanded by Marshal Moncey. However, Napoleon transferred command to Marshal [[Jean Lannes]] when the advance began. This corps was just under 34,000 men consisting of four infantry divisions and three cavalry regiments. To this was added [[General of Division]] [[Joseph Lagrange (soldier)|Joseph Lagrange]]\u2019s infantry division and [[General of Brigade]] [[Pierre David de Colbert-Chabanais]]\u2019s cavalry brigade from Ney's corps.\n\nOn the night of 22 November the French Army camped at [[Alfaro, La Rioja|Alfaro]] \u2013 17 kilometres up the Ebro from Tudela.<ref>This section is based on Rickard, J (28 February 2008), Battle of Tudela, 23 November 1808 [http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_tudela.html ]</ref>\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:Campo batalla224.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.6|Progress Plan of the Battle]]\n\nOn the morning of 23 November 1808 Lagrange's infantry and two cavalry brigades were sent towards Cascante. The rest of the force was sent along the Ebro towards Tudela.\n\nAt this time O\u2019Neylle was trying to get his three divisions across the Ebro. Roca's was across first and reached its position on the right of the Spanish line just as the French attacked.\n\nSaint-Marcq's division was second across and also took up position before the attack.\n\n[[File:Batalla224.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|Recreation of the battle on the hill of Santa Barbara with the tower of the cathedral in the background]]\n\nBy the time O\u2019Neylle's own division was crossing it had to fight French skirmishers who were at the top of the Cabezo Malla ridge.\n\nThe initial French attack was carried out in a piecemeal fashion by the vanguard when it was realised that the Spanish were not in position. Although this attack was repelled it showed the weakness of the Spanish positions, especially the {{convert|5|km|mi|0}} gap between Casta\u00f1os and La Pe\u00f1a's force at Cascante.\n\nThe battle would ultimately be decided by La Pe\u00f1a and Grimarest. By noon on 23 November 1808 they had received orders to move: La Pe\u00f1a to close the gap at Tudela and Grimarest to Cascante. Both men failed to carry out these orders other than La Pe\u00f1a moving two battalions and a detachment of provincial Grenadiers to Urzante. La Pe\u00f1a's lack of initiative allowed the two French cavalry brigades of Colbert and General of Brigade [[Alexandre, vicomte Digeon]] to pin him in place.\n \nThe second French attack was made with much greater force. On the French left General of Division [[Antoine Morlot]]\u2019s division attacked Roca's division on the heights above Tudela. On the French right General of Division [[Maurice Mathieu]]\u2019s division made a frontal assault on the smaller O\u2019Neylle division while also making outflanking moves. The attacks on both left and right were successful with both Spanish divisions being pushed off the ridges they occupied.\n\nThen the French cavalry under General of Division [[Charles Lefebvre-Desnouettes]] charged the gap between Roca and Saint-Marcq causing the collapse of the Spanish right.\n\nLa Pe\u00f1a and Grimarest finally united at Cascante late in the day giving them a total of 21,000 men against Lagrange's division which was 6,000 strong plus Colbert and Digeon. After the defeat of the rest of the Spanish army however La Pe\u00f1a and Grimarest withdrew after dark. Their poor performance was also reflected in the casualties of only 200 on the Spanish left compared to 3,000 on the right plus 1,000 prisoners.<ref>This section based on Rickard, J (28 February 2008), Battle of Tudela, 23 November 1808 [http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_tudela.html ]</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Spanish armies of the left and right escaped from Tudela in two directions. The Aragonese forces on the right made for Zaragoza where they would assist in the [[Second Siege of Zaragoza]] starting on 20 December 1808. The virtually intact Spanish left moved towards Madrid to defend that city.\n\nNapoleon however moved more quickly, and after defeating a small Spanish army at the [[Battle of Somosierra]] on 30 November 1808, arrived in Madrid on 1 December 1808.\n\nNapoleon's strategy ultimately ended in total success with Madrid in his hands. He was then able to prepare for the reconquest of Portugal.<ref>This section based on Rickard, J (28 February 2008), Battle of Tudela, 23 November 1808 [http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_tudela.html ]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|42|03|17.73|N|1|36|58.79|W|source:eswiki_region:ES_type:city|display=title}}\n\n==Other Reading==\n*''History of the Peninsular War vol.1: 1807-1809 - From the Treaty of Fontainebleau to the Battle of Corunna'', Sir Charles Oman, 704 pages, paperback, Greenhill Books, New Edition 2004, English, {{ISBN|978-1853675881}}\n\nThe first volume of Oman's classic seven volume history of the Peninsular War, this is one of the classic works of military history and provides an invaluable detailed narrative of the fighting in Spain and Portugal. This first volume covers the initial French intervention, the start of the Spanish uprising, the early British involvement in Spain and Portugal and Napoleon's own brief visit to Spain.\n\n*''The Spanish Ulcer, A History of the Peninsular War'', David Gates, Pimlico Nw Edition 2002, 592 pages, Hardcover, English, {{ISBN|978-0712697309}}\n\nAn excellent single volume history of the Peninsular War, which, when it was published, was the first really good English language history of the entire war since Oman. This is a well balanced work with detailed coverage of those campaigns conducted entirely by Spanish armies, as well as the better known British intervention in Portugal and Spain.\n\n{{Napoleonic Wars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tudela}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1808|Battle of Tudela]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Spain]]\n[[Category:Battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Poland]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Peninsular War]]\n[[Category:1808 in Spain|Battle of Tudela]]\n[[Category:November 1808 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Tudela\n|partof=the [[Peninsular War]]\n|image=La batalla de Tudela, por January Suchodolski.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=''Battle of Tudela'', an 1827 painting by [[January Suchodolski]]<br>oil on canvas, [[National Museum in Warsaw]]\n|date=23 November 1808\n|place=[[Tudela, Navarre|Tudela]], [[Kingdom of Navarre|Navarre]], [[Spain]]\n|result=Franco-Polish victory\n|combatant1={{flagicon|France}} [[First French Empire|French Empire]]<br>{{flagicon|Poland}} [[Duchy of Warsaw]]\n|combatant2={{flag|Spain|1785}}\n|commander1={{flagicon|France}} [[Jean Lannes|Marshal Lannes]]<br>{{flagicon|France}} [[Michel Ney|Marshal Ney]]<br>{{flagicon|France}} [[Charles Lefebvre-Desnouettes|General Lefebvre-Desnouettes]]\n|commander2={{flagicon|Spain|1785}} [[Francisco Javier Casta\u00f1os, 1st Duke of Bail\u00e9n|Duke of Bail\u00e9n]]<br>{{flagicon|Spain|1785}} [[Jos\u00e9 Rebolledo de Palafox, 1st Duke of Saragossa|Duke of Saragossa]]<br>{{flagicon|Spain|1785}} [[Juan O'Neylle|General O'Neylle]]<br>{{flagicon|Spain|1785}} [[Manuel la Pe\u00f1a|General La Pe\u00f1a]]<br>{{flagicon|Spain|1785}} General Grimarest\n|strength1=31,000 \n|strength2=33,000\n|casualties1=650 killed or wounded\n|casualties2=4,000 killed, wounded, or captured<br>26 guns lost\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Peninsular War (1808-1809)}}\n{{Campaignbox Peninsular War}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Tudela''' (23 November 1808) saw an [[First French Empire|Imperial French]] army led by [[Marshal of France|Marshal]] [[Jean Lannes]] attack a [[Kingdom of Spain|Spanish]] army under [[Francisco Javier Casta\u00f1os, 1st Duke of Bail\u00e9n|General Casta\u00f1os]]. The battle resulted in the complete victory of the Imperial forces over their adversaries. The combat occurred near [[Tudela, Navarre|Tudela in Navarre]], [[Spain]] during the [[Peninsular War]], part of a wider conflict known as the [[Napoleonic Wars]].\n\nSpanish casualties were estimated to be about 4,000 dead and 3,000 prisoners out of a total force of 33,000. The French and Poles lost no more than 650 dead and wounded out of a total of 31,000. This is one of the battles whose name was engraved on the [[Arc de Triomphe]] in [[Paris]].<ref>[http://arcdetriomphe.info/battles/tudela/ Arc de Triomphe website]</ref>\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Dos de Mayo Uprising]] of 2 May 1808, followed by extensive uprisings throughout Spain, forced the French to pull back from their occupation of Spain to the [[Ebro]] River. There was an opportunity for the Spanish to finally expel the French altogether but this was missed due to their failure to appoint a Supreme Commander leaving the individual Spanish forces to operate independently.\n\nThese Spanish forces consisted of the army of General [[Joaqu\u00edn Blake]] on the North coast, the army of General [[Francisco Javier Casta\u00f1os, 1st Duke of Bail\u00e9n|Francisco Javier Casta\u00f1os]] around [[Tudela, Navarre|Tudela]] and the army of General [[Jos\u00e9 Rebolledo de Palafox, 1st Duke of Saragossa|Jos\u00e9 Rebolledo de Palafox]] around [[Zaragoza]]. Blake was active in attacking the French but his offensive near [[Bilbao]] was defeated at [[Battle of Pancorbo (1808)|Pancorbo]] on 31 October 1808.\n\n[[Napoleon]]\u2019s strategy was to make a strong attack towards [[Burgos]] splitting off the army of Blake from the others and to outflank them by then swinging both north and south. It was in his interest that the Spanish maintain their exposed advanced positions. The French armies facing them were therefore ordered not to attack. So from October to 21 November 1808, Marshal [[Bon-Adrien Jeannot de Moncey]]\u2019s [[III Corps (Grande Arm\u00e9e)|III Corps]] remained static in front of Casta\u00f1os's army.\n\nThe Spanish armies were however in a constant state of movement to no effect. For much of the time Casta\u00f1os was ill leaving Palafox to direct operations. Palafox seems to have been indecisive on what course of action to take.<ref>This section is based on Rickard, J (28 February 2008), Battle of Tudela, 23 November 1808 [http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_tudela.html ]</ref>\n\n==Battlefield==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=September 2014}}\nThe battlefield was the area between Tudela and the neighbouring hills on the left. The Spanish front was deployed on the hills of Santa Barbara, Tudela, Torre Monreal, Santa Quiteria the top of Cabezoe Maya (the hill where the retreat of San Juan de Calchetas was), and the villages of Urzante (now disappeared), [[Murchante]], and [[Cascante]]. Separating the Spanish and the French was the [[Queiles]] River, a tributary of the [[Ebro]].\n\nThe French advanced from the Cierzo hills that were in front of the Spanish lines towards the Spanish troops.\n\n==Preliminaries==\nOn 21 November 1808 Casta\u00f1os was around [[Calahorra]] on the Ebro between [[Logrono]] and Tudela. On this day the French III Corps crossed the Ebro at Logrono and headed east towards Calahorra while at the same time Marshal [[Michel Ney]] with the [[VI Corps (Grande Arm\u00e9e)|VI Corps]] reached the Upper [[Douro]] Valley and headed towards Tudela.\n\n[[File:Esquema posiciones224.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.6|Diagram of Spanish positions: Santa Barbara - La Pe\u00f1a Division]]\n\nThese movements threatened Casta\u00f1os with entrapment between these two armies. To avoid this Casta\u00f1os withdrew to Tudela. He decided to defend a line {{convert|17|km|mi|0}} long stretching west from Tudela along the Ebro, then along the [[Queiles]] River to [[Cascante]] and finally to [[Tarazona]] at the foot of the [[Moncayo Massif]].\n\nCasta\u00f1os had insufficient men to hold a line of this length so he asked General [[Juan O'Neylle]], who had two divisions at [[Caparroso]] on the east bank of the Ebro, for help. As O\u2019Neylle was under the command of Palafox he refused to move without an order from Palafox. This did not arrive until noon on 22 November 1808. O\u2019Neylle moved promptly to the east bank of the Ebro opposite Tudela but decided not to cross the river until the next day.\n\nBy nightfall on 22 November 1808 Casta\u00f1os had almost 45,000 soldiers in the vicinity of Tudela but very few of them actually in position. Casta\u00f1os placed General [[Manuel la Pe\u00f1a]]\u2019s 4th Division of 8,000 men, mostly [[Andalusian people|Andalusians]] who had participated in the [[Battle of Bail\u00e9n]], at [[Cascante]] and General Grimarest at the head of three divisions totaling 13,000 to 14,000 soldiers at Tarazona. General Roca's division was on the east bank of the Ebro plus the two divisions from Aragon of O\u2019Neylle and [[Felipe Augusto de Saint-Marcq]].<ref>[http://www.aulamilitar.com/pagiht17.htm El regimiento de voluntarios de Segorbe (1808\u20131809) [[File:Flag of Spain (1785-1873 and 1875-1931).svg|20px]](Es)]</ref>\n\nMost of the fighting in the battle of Tudela would involve only the three divisions of Roca, O\u2019Neylle, and Saint-Marcq \u2013 totaling about 23,000 infantry.\n\nFor the French only the III Corps was involved in the Battle of Tudela. Prior to 22 November 1808 this force had been commanded by Marshal Moncey. However, Napoleon transferred command to Marshal [[Jean Lannes]] when the advance began. This corps was just under 34,000 men consisting of four infantry divisions and three cavalry regiments. To this was added [[General of Division]] [[Joseph Lagrange (soldier)|Joseph Lagrange]]\u2019s infantry division and [[General of Brigade]] [[Pierre David de Colbert-Chabanais]]\u2019s cavalry brigade from Ney's corps.\n\nOn the night of 22 November the French Army camped at [[Alfaro, La Rioja|Alfaro]] \u2013 17 kilometres up the Ebro from Tudela.<ref>This section is based on Rickard, J (28 February 2008), Battle of Tudela, 23 November 1808 [http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_tudela.html ]</ref>\n\n==Battle==\n[[File:Campo batalla224.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.6|Progress Plan of the Battle]]\n\nOn the morning of 23 November 1808 Lagrange's infantry and two cavalry brigades were sent towards Cascante. The rest of the force was sent along the Ebro towards Tudela.\n\nAt this time O\u2019Neylle was trying to get his three divisions across the Ebro. Roca's was across first and reached its position on the right of the Spanish line just as the French attacked.\n\nSaint-Marcq's division was second across and also took up position before the attack.\n\n[[File:Batalla224.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|Recreation of the battle on the hill of Santa Barbara with the tower of the cathedral in the background]]\n\nBy the time O\u2019Neylle's own division was crossing it had to fight French skirmishers who were at the top of the Cabezo Malla ridge.\n\nThe initial French attack was carried out in a piecemeal fashion by the vanguard when it was realised that the Spanish were not in position. Although this attack was repelled it showed the weakness of the Spanish positions, especially the {{convert|5|km|mi|0}} gap between Casta\u00f1os and La Pe\u00f1a's force at Cascante.\n\nThe battle would ultimately be decided by La Pe\u00f1a and Grimarest. By noon on 23 November 1808 they had received orders to move: La Pe\u00f1a to close the gap at Tudela and Grimarest to Cascante. Both men failed to carry out these orders other than La Pe\u00f1a moving two battalions and a detachment of provincial Grenadiers to Urzante. La Pe\u00f1a's lack of initiative allowed the two French cavalry brigades of Colbert and General of Brigade [[Alexandre, vicomte Digeon]] to pin him in place.\n \nThe second French attack was made with much greater force. On the French left General of Division [[Antoine Morlot]]\u2019s division attacked Roca's division on the heights above Tudela. On the French right General of Division [[Maurice Mathieu]]\u2019s division made a frontal assault on the smaller O\u2019Neylle division while also making outflanking moves. The attacks on both left and right were successful with both Spanish divisions being pushed off the ridges they occupied.\n\nThen the French cavalry under General of Division [[Charles Lefebvre-Desnouettes]] charged the gap between Roca and Saint-Marcq causing the collapse of the Spanish right.\n\nLa Pe\u00f1a and Grimarest finally united at Cascante late in the day giving them a total of 21,000 men against Lagrange's division which was 6,000 strong plus Colbert and Digeon. After the defeat of the rest of the Spanish army however La Pe\u00f1a and Grimarest withdrew after dark. Their poor performance was also reflected in the casualties of only 200 on the Spanish left compared to 3,000 on the right plus 1,000 prisoners.<ref>This section based on Rickard, J (28 February 2008), Battle of Tudela, 23 November 1808 [http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_tudela.html ]</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Spanish armies of the left and right escaped from Tudela in two directions. The Aragonese forces on the right made for Zaragoza where they would assist in the [[Second Siege of Zaragoza]] starting on 20 December 1808. The virtually intact Spanish left moved towards Madrid to defend that city.\n\nNapoleon however moved more quickly, and after defeating a small Spanish army at the [[Battle of Somosierra]] on 30 November 1808, arrived in Madrid on 1 December 1808.\n\nNapoleon's strategy ultimately ended in total success with Madrid in his hands. He was then able to prepare for the reconquest of Portugal.<ref>This section based on Rickard, J (28 February 2008), Battle of Tudela, 23 November 1808 [http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_tudela.html ]</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|42|03|17.73|N|1|36|58.79|W|source:eswiki_region:ES_type:city|display=title}}\n\n==Other Reading==\n*''History of the Peninsular War vol.1: 1807-1809 - From the Treaty of Fontainebleau to the Battle of Corunna'', Sir Charles Oman, 704 pages, paperback, Greenhill Books, New Edition 2004, English, {{ISBN|978-1853675881}}\n\nThe first volume of Oman's classic seven volume history of the Peninsular War, this is one of the classic works of military history and provides an invaluable detailed narrative of the fighting in Spain and Portugal. This first volume covers the initial French intervention, the start of the Spanish uprising, the early British involvement in Spain and Portugal and Napoleon's own brief visit to Spain.\n\n*''The Spanish Ulcer, A History of the Peninsular War'', David Gates, Pimlico Nw Edition 2002, 592 pages, Hardcover, English, {{ISBN|978-0712697309}}\n\nAn excellent single volume history of the Peninsular War, which, when it was published, was the first really good English language history of the entire war since Oman. This is a well balanced work with detailed coverage of those campaigns conducted entirely by Spanish armies, as well as the better known British intervention in Portugal and Spain.\n\n{{Napoleonic Wars}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tudela}}\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1808|Battle of Tudela]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Spain]]\n[[Category:Battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Poland]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Peninsular War]]\n[[Category:1808 in Spain|Battle of Tudela]]\n[[Category:November 1808 events]]\n", "name_user": "Snagemit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Infobox changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Tudela"}
{"title_page": "Fulbright University Vietnam", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name = Fulbright University Vietnam\n| native_name = \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Ph\u01b0\u01a1ng Mai Vi\u1ec7t Nam\n| native_name_lang = vie\n|image_size =\n|established = {{start date|2016}}\n|type = Private nonprofit\n|endowment =\n|president = \u0110\u00e0m B\u00edch Th\u1ee7y<ref>{{cite web|title=Fulbright University Vietnam ensures global quality for local students: president|url=http://tuoitrenews.vn/education/30097/fulbright-university-vietnam-ensures-global-quality-for-local-students-president|work=[[Tuoi Tre News]]|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tr\u01b0\u1eddng \u0110H Fulbright Vi\u1ec7t Nam nh\u1eadn gi\u1ea5y ph\u00e9p th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp|url=http://nld.com.vn/thoi-su-trong-nuoc/truong-dh-fulbright-viet-nam-nhan-giay-phep-thanh-lap-20160525093446547.htm|work=[[Ng\u01b0\u1eddi Lao \u0110\u1ed9ng]]|date=May 25, 2015|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n|undergrad = \n|postgrad = \n|city = [[Ho Chi Minh City]]\n|country = [[Vietnam]]\n|website = {{url|http://www.fulbright.edu.vn}}\n|image_name =\n|faculty = \n}}\n'''Fulbright University Vietnam''' ('''FUV''') is a private nonprofit university in the [[Saigon Hi-Tech Park]] in [[Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fulbright University Vietnam|url=http://www.tuiv.org/fulbright-university-vietnam.html|publisher=Trust for University Innovation|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> It is one of Vietnam's first private, nonprofit institutions of higher education.<ref name=\"Harvard\">{{cite web|title=A New University for Vietnam|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2014/06/harvard-affiliated-university-vietnam|work=[[Harvard Magazine]]|date=June 20, 2014|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> The FUV concept emerged from discussions convened by the Vietnam Program at the Harvard Kennedy School aimed at planning the next stage in the development of the [http://www.fetp.edu.vn Fulbright Economics Teaching Program (FETP)], a center of public policy research and teaching in Ho Chi Minh City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/our-story/|title=Our Story {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2014/05/a-nation-building|title=A Nation, Building|date=2014-04-11|newspaper=Harvard Magazine|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> Since 2014, the university's development has been coordinated by the [[Trust for University Innovation in Vietnam (TUIV)]], a nonprofit corporation based in the Boston area. TUIV and the Harvard Vietnam Program are recipients of several grants from the Bureau of Educational and Cultural Affairs of the United States Department of State. <ref name=\"Thanh Nien\"/>\n\n==History==\nAlthough Fulbright University Vietnam is a private university, it has benefited from the support of the governments of both Vietnam and the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2014/05/a-nation-building|title=A Nation, Building|date=2014-04-11|newspaper=Harvard Magazine|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/special-reports/157084/john-kerry-and-the-journey-of-fulbright-university-vietnam.html|title=John Kerry and the journey of Fulbright University Vietnam - News VietNamNet|last=vietnamnet.vn|website=english.vietnamnet.vn|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> In the United States, Fulbright University Vietnam, and its antecedent, the Fulbright Economics Teaching Program, has benefited from strong bilateral support in Congress. Of particular note is the role played by [[John Kerry]]. While in the Senate, Kerry and his fellow Vietnam veteran John McCain were strong supporters of education exchange with Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2014/05/a-nation-building|title=A Nation, Building|date=2014-04-11|newspaper=Harvard Magazine|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> As Secretary of State, Kerry was an early advocate for the FUV initiative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2013/12/218721.htm|title=Remarks to Ho Chi Minh City Business Community and Fulbright Economic Teaching Program Participants|newspaper=U.S. Department of State|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, FUV was cited in a joint statement by [[President of Vietnam|President]] [[Truong Tan Sang]] and [[Barack Obama|President Barack Obama]] during President Sang's visit to the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/25/joint-statement-president-barack-obama-united-states-america-and-preside|title=Joint Statement by President Barack Obama of the United States of America and President Truong Tan Sang of the Socialist Republic of Vietnam|date=2013-07-25|newspaper=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> In June 2014, [[Prime Minister of Vietnam|Prime Minister]] [[Nguy\u1ec5n T\u1ea5n D\u0169ng]] approved the establishment of FUV.<ref name=\"FETP\">{{cite web|title=Vietnamese PM approves in principle TUIV\u2019s establishment of Fulbright University Vietnam (FUV)|url=http://www.fetp.edu.vn/en/news-events/on-campus/vietnamese-pm-approves-in-principle-tuiv%E2%80%99s-establishment-of-fulbright-university-vietnam-fuv/|publisher=[[Fulbright Economics Teaching Program]]|date=June 5, 2014|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> In December 2014, the [[United States Congress]] approved $20 million to fund the development of FUV on the condition that the university be independent, not-for-profit, and on par with the quality of American universities.<ref name=\"Vietnamnet\">{{cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/special-reports/157084/john-kerry-and-the-journey-of-fulbright-university-vietnam.html|title=John Kerry and the journey of Fulbright University Vietnam|date=May 27, 2016|work=VietNamNet|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Thanh Nien\" />\n\nThe [[government of Vietnam]] officially licensed FUV on May 16, 2016.<ref name=\"Thanh Nien\">{{cite web|last=Anh|first=Ha|title=\nUS non-profit university Fulbright launched in Vietnam|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/education-youth/us-nonprofit-university-fulbright-launched-in-vietnam-62557.html|work=[[Thanh Ni\u00ean News]]|date=May 25, 2016|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> Later that month, the launch of Fulbright University Vietnam was officially announced in a speech by President [[Barack Obama]] in Hanoi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2016/05/24/remarks-president-obama-address-people-vietnam|title=Remarks by President Obama in Address to the People of Vietnam|date=2016-05-24|newspaper=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> Two days later in Ho Chi Minh City, at a ceremony witness by Secretary of State John Kerry, Fulbright University VIetnam was awarded its establishment license.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/education-youth/us-nonprofit-university-fulbright-launched-in-vietnam-62557.html|title=US non-profit university Fulbright launched in Vietnam|date=2016-05-25|newspaper=Thanh Nien Daily|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n== Vision ==\nAlthough Fulbright University Vietnam is inspired by the American liberal education tradition, it is not an attempt to recreate an American university in Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/vision-4/|title=Vision {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> Distinguishing features of FUV's approach include, in its institutional design, a commitment to innovation, not replication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/vision-4/|title=Vision {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> FUV is also dedicated to serving Vietnamese society. This commitment to service is reflected in its emphasis on recruiting students of diverse socioeconomic backgrounds and to providing need-based financial assistance. It is also manifested in its aspiration to help address challenges facing Vietnam and the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/opportunity/|title=Opportunity {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nDuring its first five years, FUV will focus on the development of two integrated academic units, a graduate school of public policy and management and an undergraduate program in engineering and the liberal arts and sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/opportunity/|title=Opportunity {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Fulbright School of Public Policy and Management''' represents the continuation and expansion of the Fulbright Economics Teaching Program, the center of public policy teaching and research operated by the Harvard Kennedy School Vietnam Program from 1994 to 2016. The public policy school will offer degree and non-degree programs in public policy and related fields. \n\nFUV's '''undergraduate program in engineering and the liberal arts and sciences''' is scheduled to admit a beta class in 2018. This program is being developed in collaboration with faculty members from the [[Franklin W. Olin College of Engineering|Olin College of Engineering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/the-design-team/|title=The Design Team {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> The undergraduate program will feature interdisciplinary courses, project-based learning, and active engagement with the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/opportunity/|title=Opportunity {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> \n\nFUV intends to seek accreditation from a US regional accrediting body. FUV may enroll up to 2,000 students during its first five years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/special-reports/157084/john-kerry-and-the-journey-of-fulbright-university-vietnam.html|title=John Kerry and the journey of Fulbright University Vietnam - News VietNamNet|last=vietnamnet.vn|website=english.vietnamnet.vn|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nFUV plans to build its main campus in the [[Saigon Hi-Tech Park]] in District 9. The government of Ho Chi Minh City has contributed 15 hectares of land in the park to FUV, where FUV will build learning and residential facilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/special-reports/157084/john-kerry-and-the-journey-of-fulbright-university-vietnam.html|title=John Kerry and the journey of Fulbright University Vietnam - News VietNamNet|last=vietnamnet.vn|website=english.vietnamnet.vn|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==The Bob Kerrey Controversy==\n\nIn May 2016 during his visit to Vietnam, then Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] announced that the Americans had appointed \n[[Bob Kerrey]] to be Chairman of the Board of Trustees of Fulbright University Vietnam.  This gave rise to the controversy.<ref>Richard C. Paddock, \"War Record Fuels Debate Over University Appointment in Vietnam,\" 3 June 2016,\nhttps://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/03/world/asia/vietnam-fulbright-university-kerrey.html</ref>  In 2001 an in-depth investigation by ''The New York Times'' and CBS News<ref>Greg Vistica, \"One Awful Night in Thanh Phong,\" 25 April 2001, https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/25/magazine/one-awful-night-in-thanh-phong.html</ref> had revealed that on 25 February 1969 Bob Kerrey had commanded a Navy SEALS unit that massacred 21 civilians in [[Bob Kerrey#Thanh Phong raid|Th\u1ea1nh Phong]] village.  \n\nAmong the prominent Vietnamese critics of the appointment of Kerrey were {{ill|T\u00f4n N\u1eef Th\u1ecb Ninh|vi}}, a former ambassador to the European Union,<ref>Ton Nhu Thi Ninh, \"Bob Kerrey in Vietnam,\" 8 June 2016, https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/08/opinion/bob-kerrey-in-vietnam.html</ref> and [[Viet Thanh Nguyen|Nguy\u1ec5n Thanh Vi\u1ec7t]], an award-winning Vietnamese-American \nwriter.<ref>Viet Thanh Nguyen, \"Bob Kerrey and the 'American Tragedy' of Vietnam,\" 20 June 2016, https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/20/opinion/bob-kerrey-and-the-american-tragedy-of-vietnam.html</ref> The most high-ranking Vietnamese official to publicly support Kerrey's appointment was [[\u0110inh La Th\u0103ng]],<ref>\u0110inh La Th\u0103ng, 4 June 2016, https://tuoitrenews.vn/society/35192/hcmc-leader-calls-for-rising-above-hatred-in-debate-of-bob-kerreys-role-at-fuv</ref>\nwho at the time was Communist Party Secretary of Ho Chi Minh City and a member of the Politburo.\n\nIn May 2017, it is reported that Bob Kerrey had stepped down from the position of Chairman of Fulbright Board of Trustees.<ref name=\"Ashwill\">Mark Ashwill, 26 May 2017, https://www.counterpunch.org/2017/05/26/the-fat-lady-finally-sings-bob-kerrey-quietly-resigns-from-fulbright-university-vietnam-leadership-position/</ref>  In May 2018, [[H. Kim Bottomly]], former president of [[Wellesley College]], was appointed as the chair of the board of the trustees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/fulbright-university-vietnam-assigns-new-chair-to-replace-controversial-predecessor-3744006.html|title=Fulbright University Vietnam assigns new chair to replace controversial predecessor - VnExpress International|last=VnExpress|website=VnExpress International \u2013 Latest news, business, travel and analysis from Vietnam|language=en|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[http://www.tuiv.org/fulbright-university-vietnam.html Fulbright University Vietnam]\n\n{{coord missing|Vietnam}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fulbright University Vietnam}}\n[[Category:United States\u2013Vietnam relations]]\n[[Category:Universities in Ho Chi Minh City]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2016]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State]]\n[[Category:Bureau of Educational and Cultural Affairs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n|name = Fulbright University Vietnam\n| native_name = \u0110\u1ea1i h\u1ecdc Fulbright Di\u1ec7t N\u01a1m\n| native_name_lang = vie\n|image_size =\n|established = {{start date|2016}}\n|type = Private nonprofit\n|endowment =\n|president = \u0110\u00e0m B\u00edch Th\u1ee7y<ref>{{cite web|title=Fulbright University Vietnam ensures global quality for local students: president|url=http://tuoitrenews.vn/education/30097/fulbright-university-vietnam-ensures-global-quality-for-local-students-president|work=[[Tuoi Tre News]]|date=August 28, 2015|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Tr\u01b0\u1eddng \u0110H Fulbright Vi\u1ec7t Nam nh\u1eadn gi\u1ea5y ph\u00e9p th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp|url=http://nld.com.vn/thoi-su-trong-nuoc/truong-dh-fulbright-viet-nam-nhan-giay-phep-thanh-lap-20160525093446547.htm|work=[[Ng\u01b0\u1eddi Lao \u0110\u1ed9ng]]|date=May 25, 2015|accessdate=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n|undergrad = \n|postgrad = \n|city = [[Ho Chi Minh City]]\n|country = [[Vietnam]]\n|website = {{url|http://www.fulbright.edu.vn}}\n|image_name =\n|faculty = \n}}\n'''Fulbright University Vietnam''' ('''FUV''') is a private nonprofit university in the [[Saigon Hi-Tech Park]] in [[Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fulbright University Vietnam|url=http://www.tuiv.org/fulbright-university-vietnam.html|publisher=Trust for University Innovation|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> It is one of Vietnam's first private, nonprofit institutions of higher education.<ref name=\"Harvard\">{{cite web|title=A New University for Vietnam|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2014/06/harvard-affiliated-university-vietnam|work=[[Harvard Magazine]]|date=June 20, 2014|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> The FUV concept emerged from discussions convened by the Vietnam Program at the Harvard Kennedy School aimed at planning the next stage in the development of the [http://www.fetp.edu.vn Fulbright Economics Teaching Program (FETP)], a center of public policy research and teaching in Ho Chi Minh City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/our-story/|title=Our Story {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2014/05/a-nation-building|title=A Nation, Building|date=2014-04-11|newspaper=Harvard Magazine|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> Since 2014, the university's development has been coordinated by the [[Trust for University Innovation in Vietnam (TUIV)]], a nonprofit corporation based in the Boston area. TUIV and the Harvard Vietnam Program are recipients of several grants from the Bureau of Educational and Cultural Affairs of the United States Department of State. <ref name=\"Thanh Nien\"/>\n\n==History==\nAlthough Fulbright University Vietnam is a private university, it has benefited from the support of the governments of both Vietnam and the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2014/05/a-nation-building|title=A Nation, Building|date=2014-04-11|newspaper=Harvard Magazine|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/special-reports/157084/john-kerry-and-the-journey-of-fulbright-university-vietnam.html|title=John Kerry and the journey of Fulbright University Vietnam - News VietNamNet|last=vietnamnet.vn|website=english.vietnamnet.vn|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> In the United States, Fulbright University Vietnam, and its antecedent, the Fulbright Economics Teaching Program, has benefited from strong bilateral support in Congress. Of particular note is the role played by [[John Kerry]]. While in the Senate, Kerry and his fellow Vietnam veteran John McCain were strong supporters of education exchange with Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2014/05/a-nation-building|title=A Nation, Building|date=2014-04-11|newspaper=Harvard Magazine|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> As Secretary of State, Kerry was an early advocate for the FUV initiative.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2013/12/218721.htm|title=Remarks to Ho Chi Minh City Business Community and Fulbright Economic Teaching Program Participants|newspaper=U.S. Department of State|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, FUV was cited in a joint statement by [[President of Vietnam|President]] [[Truong Tan Sang]] and [[Barack Obama|President Barack Obama]] during President Sang's visit to the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/25/joint-statement-president-barack-obama-united-states-america-and-preside|title=Joint Statement by President Barack Obama of the United States of America and President Truong Tan Sang of the Socialist Republic of Vietnam|date=2013-07-25|newspaper=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> In June 2014, [[Prime Minister of Vietnam|Prime Minister]] [[Nguy\u1ec5n T\u1ea5n D\u0169ng]] approved the establishment of FUV.<ref name=\"FETP\">{{cite web|title=Vietnamese PM approves in principle TUIV\u2019s establishment of Fulbright University Vietnam (FUV)|url=http://www.fetp.edu.vn/en/news-events/on-campus/vietnamese-pm-approves-in-principle-tuiv%E2%80%99s-establishment-of-fulbright-university-vietnam-fuv/|publisher=[[Fulbright Economics Teaching Program]]|date=June 5, 2014|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> In December 2014, the [[United States Congress]] approved $20 million to fund the development of FUV on the condition that the university be independent, not-for-profit, and on par with the quality of American universities.<ref name=\"Vietnamnet\">{{cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/special-reports/157084/john-kerry-and-the-journey-of-fulbright-university-vietnam.html|title=John Kerry and the journey of Fulbright University Vietnam|date=May 27, 2016|work=VietNamNet|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Thanh Nien\" />\n\nThe [[government of Vietnam]] officially licensed FUV on May 16, 2016.<ref name=\"Thanh Nien\">{{cite web|last=Anh|first=Ha|title=\nUS non-profit university Fulbright launched in Vietnam|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/education-youth/us-nonprofit-university-fulbright-launched-in-vietnam-62557.html|work=[[Thanh Ni\u00ean News]]|date=May 25, 2016|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> Later that month, the launch of Fulbright University Vietnam was officially announced in a speech by President [[Barack Obama]] in Hanoi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2016/05/24/remarks-president-obama-address-people-vietnam|title=Remarks by President Obama in Address to the People of Vietnam|date=2016-05-24|newspaper=whitehouse.gov|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> Two days later in Ho Chi Minh City, at a ceremony witness by Secretary of State John Kerry, Fulbright University VIetnam was awarded its establishment license.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/education-youth/us-nonprofit-university-fulbright-launched-in-vietnam-62557.html|title=US non-profit university Fulbright launched in Vietnam|date=2016-05-25|newspaper=Thanh Nien Daily|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n== Vision ==\nAlthough Fulbright University Vietnam is inspired by the American liberal education tradition, it is not an attempt to recreate an American university in Vietnam.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/vision-4/|title=Vision {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> Distinguishing features of FUV's approach include, in its institutional design, a commitment to innovation, not replication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/vision-4/|title=Vision {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> FUV is also dedicated to serving Vietnamese society. This commitment to service is reflected in its emphasis on recruiting students of diverse socioeconomic backgrounds and to providing need-based financial assistance. It is also manifested in its aspiration to help address challenges facing Vietnam and the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/opportunity/|title=Opportunity {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nDuring its first five years, FUV will focus on the development of two integrated academic units, a graduate school of public policy and management and an undergraduate program in engineering and the liberal arts and sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/opportunity/|title=Opportunity {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nThe '''Fulbright School of Public Policy and Management''' represents the continuation and expansion of the Fulbright Economics Teaching Program, the center of public policy teaching and research operated by the Harvard Kennedy School Vietnam Program from 1994 to 2016. The public policy school will offer degree and non-degree programs in public policy and related fields. \n\nFUV's '''undergraduate program in engineering and the liberal arts and sciences''' is scheduled to admit a beta class in 2018. This program is being developed in collaboration with faculty members from the [[Franklin W. Olin College of Engineering|Olin College of Engineering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/the-design-team/|title=The Design Team {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> The undergraduate program will feature interdisciplinary courses, project-based learning, and active engagement with the community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuiv.org/opportunity/|title=Opportunity {{!}} tuiv.org|website=www.tuiv.org|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref> \n\nFUV intends to seek accreditation from a US regional accrediting body. FUV may enroll up to 2,000 students during its first five years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/special-reports/157084/john-kerry-and-the-journey-of-fulbright-university-vietnam.html|title=John Kerry and the journey of Fulbright University Vietnam - News VietNamNet|last=vietnamnet.vn|website=english.vietnamnet.vn|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n== Campus ==\nFUV plans to build its main campus in the [[Saigon Hi-Tech Park]] in District 9. The government of Ho Chi Minh City has contributed 15 hectares of land in the park to FUV, where FUV will build learning and residential facilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://english.vietnamnet.vn/fms/special-reports/157084/john-kerry-and-the-journey-of-fulbright-university-vietnam.html|title=John Kerry and the journey of Fulbright University Vietnam - News VietNamNet|last=vietnamnet.vn|website=english.vietnamnet.vn|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==The Bob Kerrey Controversy==\n\nIn May 2016 during his visit to Vietnam, then Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] announced that the Americans had appointed \n[[Bob Kerrey]] to be Chairman of the Board of Trustees of Fulbright University Vietnam.  This gave rise to the controversy.<ref>Richard C. Paddock, \"War Record Fuels Debate Over University Appointment in Vietnam,\" 3 June 2016,\nhttps://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/03/world/asia/vietnam-fulbright-university-kerrey.html</ref>  In 2001 an in-depth investigation by ''The New York Times'' and CBS News<ref>Greg Vistica, \"One Awful Night in Thanh Phong,\" 25 April 2001, https://www.nytimes.com/2001/04/25/magazine/one-awful-night-in-thanh-phong.html</ref> had revealed that on 25 February 1969 Bob Kerrey had commanded a Navy SEALS unit that massacred 21 civilians in [[Bob Kerrey#Thanh Phong raid|Th\u1ea1nh Phong]] village.  \n\nAmong the prominent Vietnamese critics of the appointment of Kerrey were {{ill|T\u00f4n N\u1eef Th\u1ecb Ninh|vi}}, a former ambassador to the European Union,<ref>Ton Nhu Thi Ninh, \"Bob Kerrey in Vietnam,\" 8 June 2016, https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/08/opinion/bob-kerrey-in-vietnam.html</ref> and [[Viet Thanh Nguyen|Nguy\u1ec5n Thanh Vi\u1ec7t]], an award-winning Vietnamese-American \nwriter.<ref>Viet Thanh Nguyen, \"Bob Kerrey and the 'American Tragedy' of Vietnam,\" 20 June 2016, https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/20/opinion/bob-kerrey-and-the-american-tragedy-of-vietnam.html</ref> The most high-ranking Vietnamese official to publicly support Kerrey's appointment was [[\u0110inh La Th\u0103ng]],<ref>\u0110inh La Th\u0103ng, 4 June 2016, https://tuoitrenews.vn/society/35192/hcmc-leader-calls-for-rising-above-hatred-in-debate-of-bob-kerreys-role-at-fuv</ref>\nwho at the time was Communist Party Secretary of Ho Chi Minh City and a member of the Politburo.\n\nIn May 2017, it is reported that Bob Kerrey had stepped down from the position of Chairman of Fulbright Board of Trustees.<ref name=\"Ashwill\">Mark Ashwill, 26 May 2017, https://www.counterpunch.org/2017/05/26/the-fat-lady-finally-sings-bob-kerrey-quietly-resigns-from-fulbright-university-vietnam-leadership-position/</ref>  In May 2018, [[H. Kim Bottomly]], former president of [[Wellesley College]], was appointed as the chair of the board of the trustees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://e.vnexpress.net/news/news/fulbright-university-vietnam-assigns-new-chair-to-replace-controversial-predecessor-3744006.html|title=Fulbright University Vietnam assigns new chair to replace controversial predecessor - VnExpress International|last=VnExpress|website=VnExpress International \u2013 Latest news, business, travel and analysis from Vietnam|language=en|access-date=2018-12-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[http://www.tuiv.org/fulbright-university-vietnam.html Fulbright University Vietnam]\n\n{{coord missing|Vietnam}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fulbright University Vietnam}}\n[[Category:United States\u2013Vietnam relations]]\n[[Category:Universities in Ho Chi Minh City]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2016]]\n[[Category:United States Department of State]]\n[[Category:Bureau of Educational and Cultural Affairs]]\n", "name_user": "Lam thanh hao 135B", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fulbright_University_Vietnam"}
{"title_page": "Conan and the Amazon", "text_new": "{{short description|Book by John Maddox Roberts}}\n{{Infobox book| <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = Conan and the Amazon\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = Conanand the Amazon.jpg\n| caption       = Cover of first edition\n| author        = [[John Maddox Roberts]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  = [[Ken Kelly (artist)|Ken Kelly]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = [[Conan the Barbarian]]\n| genre         = [[Sword and sorcery]] \n| publisher     = [[Tor Books]]\n| release_date  = 1995\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print (Paperback)\n| pages         = 276\n| isbn          = 0-8125-2493-4\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n'''''Conan and the Amazon''''' is a [[fantasy literature|fantasy]] novel  by American writer [[John Maddox Roberts]], featuring [[Robert E. Howard]]'s  [[sword and sorcery]] hero [[Conan the Barbarian]]. It was first published in paperback by [[Tor Books]] in April 1995. It was reprinted by Tor in April 1999.<ref>{{isfdb title|id=15374|title=Conan and the Amazon}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nFresh from a failed rebellion in Brythunia, in which he served as a mercenary on the opposing side, Conan joins forces with a tribe of native warriors led by Achilea (former queen of the Amazons). Achilea is guiding a pair of mysterious twins in their search the ancient city of Jangar. The warriors travel across Zamora, Koth, and the Stygian Desert before crossing a range of southeastern mountains.\n\nConan's allies eventually reach the city, cursed by the gods after an ancient battle. Jangar is still in good condition despite its supposed desertion and was, in fact, never abandoned. The citizens, who loathe the sun, live within a subterranean city beneath the ruins of their old one.\n\nCaught between the evil agenda of his demonic employers and the Jangarians, Conan finds himself trapped in his battle with a giant crocodile as the city approaches its eventual destruction.\n\n==Reception==\n[[Don D'Ammassa]], writing of Roberts' Conan novels, noted that \"[a]lthough Roberts did not recreate Howard's character exactly, making him more intellectual and less inclined to solve every problem by hitting it with a sword, his evocation of the barbaric setting is superior to that of most of the other writers contributing to the series.\"<ref name=\"D'Ammassa2006\">{{cite book|last=D'Ammassa|first=Don|title=Encyclopedia of fantasy and horror fiction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jUv5gVgSNvYC&pg=PA291|accessdate=23 August 2011|date=February 2006|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]]|isbn=978-0-8160-6192-1|pages=292}}</ref> This novel, D'Ammassa writes, \"was pretty good but it was actually the least interesting of Roberts' Conan novel[s].\"<ref name=\"DAmmassa2017\">D'Ammassa, Don. [http://dondammassa.com/R2D2017.htm#Conan_and_the_Amazon \"Conan and the Amazon\" (review). Nov. 26, 2017.]</ref>\n\nReviewer Ryan Harvey considered Roberts \"the most consistently entertaining\" of the Tor Conan authors, showing \"deft ability with storytelling and action scenes, and a thankful tendency not to overplay his hand and try to ape Robert E. Howard\u2019s style. ... However, Roberts had his down moments, and alas he stumbled at the finish line. ''Conan and the Amazon'' is the last of Roberts\u2019s Conan novels. It\u2019s also his poorest.\" He rates it \"above average for the Tor novels, [but] a disappointment for its author. It moves too slowly, and the action is jumbled into a hasty mess at the conclusion.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackgate.com/2010/09/21/pastiches-%E2%80%98r%E2%80%99-us-conan-and-the-amazon/|title=Black Gate \u00bb Articles \u00bb Pastiches \u2018R\u2019 Us: Conan and the Amazon|accessdate=Apr 29, 2020}}</ref> In another place he notes that he \"would hate to judge John Maddox Roberts based on ''Conan and the Amazon'' ... [a] poor work... from [an] otherwise skilled pastiche writer...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conan.com/invboard/index.php?showtopic=1398|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422022612/http://www.conan.com/invboard/index.php?showtopic=1398|url-status=dead|title=Harvey, Ryan. \"''Conan and the Death Lord of Thanza''\" (Review), Jan. 2, 2005.|archivedate=Apr 22, 2015|accessdate=Apr 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/r/john-maddox-roberts/conan-and-amazon.htm Fantastic Fiction entry for ''Conan and the Amazon'']\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=''[[Conan the Gladiator]]''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Conan (books)#Tor editions, 1982-2004|Tor Conan series]]<br>'''<small>(publication order)</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after=''[[Conan and the Mists of Doom]]''}}\n{{s-bef|before=''[[Conan and the Death Lord of Thanza]]''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Complete Conan Saga<br>'''<small>([[Conan chronologies#William Galen Gray chronology|William Galen Gray chronology]])</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after=\"[[The Devil in Iron]]\"}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Conan}}\n\n[[Category:1995 American novels]]\n[[Category:1995 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Conan the Barbarian novels]]\n[[Category:American fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Tor Books books]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Book by John Maddox Roberts}}\n{{Infobox book| <!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]] or [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Books]] -->\n| name          = Conan and the Amazon\n| title_orig    =\n| translator    =\n| image         = Conanand the Amazon.jpg\n| caption       = Cover of first edition\n| author        = [[John Maddox Roberts]]\n| illustrator   =\n| cover_artist  = [[Ken Kelly (artist)|Ken Kelly]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series        = [[Conan the Barbarian]]\n| genre         = [[Sword and sorcery]] \n| publisher     = [[Tor Books]]\n| release_date  = 1995\n| english_release_date =\n| media_type    = Print (Paperback)\n| pages         = 276\n| isbn          = 0-8125-2493-4\n| preceded_by   = \n| followed_by   = \n}}\n'''''Conan and the Amazon''''' is a [[fantasy literature|fantasy]] novel  by American writer [[John Maddox Roberts]], featuring [[Robert E. Howard]]'s  [[sword and sorcery]] hero [[Conan the Barbarian]]. It was first published in paperback by [[Tor Books]] in April 1995. It was reprinted by Tor in April 1999.<ref>{{isfdb title|id=15374|title=Conan and the Amazon}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nFresh from a failed rebellion in Brythunia, in which he served as a mercenary on the opposing side, Conan joins forces with a tribe of native warriors led by Achilea (former queen of the Amazons). Achilea is guiding a pair of mysterious twins in their search the ancient city of Jangar. The warriors travel across Zamora, Koth, and the Stygian Desert before crossing a range of southeastern mountains.\n\nConan's allies eventually reach the city, cursed by the gods after an ancient battle. Jangar is still in good condition despite its supposed desertion and was, in fact, never abandoned. The citizens, who loathe the sun, live within a subterranean city beneath the ruins of their old one.\n\nCaught between the evil agenda of his demonic employers and the Jangarians, Conan finds himself trapped in his battle with a giant crocodile as the city approaches its eventual destruction.\n\n==Reception==\n[[Don D'Ammassa]], writing of Roberts' Conan novels, noted that \"[a]lthough Roberts did not recreate Howard's character exactly, making him more intellectual and less inclined to solve every problem by hitting it with a sword, his evocation of the barbaric setting is superior to that of most of the other writers contributing to the series.\"<ref name=\"D'Ammassa2006\">{{cite book|last=D'Ammassa|first=Don|title=Encyclopedia of fantasy and horror fiction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jUv5gVgSNvYC&pg=PA291|accessdate=23 August 2011|date=February 2006|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing]]|isbn=978-0-8160-6192-1|pages=292}}</ref> This novel, D'Ammassa writes, \"was pretty good but it was actually the least interesting of Roberts' Conan novel[s].\"<ref name=\"DAmmassa2017\">D'Ammassa, Don. [http://dondammassa.com/R2D2017.htm#Conan_and_the_Amazon \"Conan and the Amazon\" (review). Nov. 26, 2017.]</ref>\n\nReviewer Ryan Harvey considered Roberts \"the most consistently entertaining\" of the Tor Conan authors, showing \"deft ability with storytelling and action scenes, and a thankful tendency not to overplay his hand and try to ape Robert E. Howard\u2019s style. ... However, Roberts had his down moments, and alas he stumbled at the finish line. ''Conan and the Amazon'' is the last of Roberts\u2019s Conan novels. It\u2019s also his poorest.\" He rates it \"above average for the Tor novels, [but] a disappointment for its author. It moves too slowly, and the action is jumbled into a hasty mess at the conclusion.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.blackgate.com/2010/09/21/pastiches-%E2%80%98r%E2%80%99-us-conan-and-the-amazon/|title=Black Gate \u00bb Articles \u00bb Pastiches \u2018R\u2019 Us: Conan and the Amazon|accessdate=Apr 29, 2020}}</ref> In another place he notes that he \"would hate to judge John Maddox Roberts based on ''Conan and the Amazon'' ... [a] poor work... from [an] otherwise skilled pastiche writer...\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conan.com/invboard/index.php?showtopic=1398|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422022612/http://www.conan.com/invboard/index.php?showtopic=1398|deadurl=y|title=Harvey, Ryan. \"''Conan and the Death Lord of Thanza''\" (Review), Jan. 2, 2005.|archivedate=Apr 22, 2015|accessdate=Apr 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.fantasticfiction.co.uk/r/john-maddox-roberts/conan-and-amazon.htm Fantastic Fiction entry for ''Conan and the Amazon'']\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=''[[Conan the Gladiator]]''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Conan (books)#Tor editions, 1982-2004|Tor Conan series]]<br>'''<small>(publication order)</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after=''[[Conan and the Mists of Doom]]''}}\n{{s-bef|before=''[[Conan and the Death Lord of Thanza]]''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Complete Conan Saga<br>'''<small>([[Conan chronologies#William Galen Gray chronology|William Galen Gray chronology]])</small>}}\n{{s-aft|after=\"[[The Devil in Iron]]\"}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Conan}}\n\n[[Category:1995 American novels]]\n[[Category:1995 fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Conan the Barbarian novels]]\n[[Category:American fantasy novels]]\n[[Category:Tor Books books]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed unsupported cite parameter deadurl to url-status", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conan_and_the_Amazon"}
{"title_page": "Haminu Draman", "text_new": "{{short description|Ghanaian footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Haminu Draman\n| image          = Haminu.JPG\n| image_size      = 300px\n| caption        = Haminu Draman playing for [[FC Kuban Krasnodar|Kuban]]\n| fullname       = Haminu Draman\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1986|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Techiman]], Ghana\n| height         = {{convert|1.73|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    =           |youthclubs1 =\n| years1         = 2004\u20132005 |clubs1  = [[Heart of Lions]]                       |caps1  = 3   |goals1  = 0\n| years2         = 2005\u20132006 |clubs2  = [[Red Star Belgrade]]                    |caps2  = 4   |goals2  = 1\n| years3         = 2006\u20132007 |clubs3  = [[Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K.|Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi]]   |caps3  = 31  |goals3  = 2\n| years4         = 2007\u20132011 |clubs4  = [[FC Lokomotiv Moscow|Lokomotiv Moscow]] |caps4  = 8   |goals4  = 0\n| years5         = 2009      |clubs5  = \u2192 [[FC Kuban Krasnodar|Kuban]] (loan)    |caps5  = 27  |goals5  = 3\n| years6         = 2011\u20132013 |clubs6  = [[AC Arles-Avignon|Arles-Avignon]]       |caps6  = 30  |goals6  = 2\n| years7         = 2013\u20132014 |clubs7  = [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]]         |caps7  = 3   |goals7  = 0\n| years8         = 2014      |clubs8  = [[Asante Kotoko SC|Asante Kotoko]]       |caps8  =     |goals8  =\n| years9         = 2015      |clubs9  = [[Charlotte Independence]]               |caps9  = 2   |goals9  = 0\n| years10        = 2016      |clubs10 = [[FC Infonet|Infonet]]                   |caps10 = 23  |goals10 = 3\n| nationalyears1 = 2005\u20132010 |nationalteam1 = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] |nationalcaps1 = 43 |nationalgoals1 = 4\n| pcupdate       = 13 June 2017\n| ntupdate       = 13 June 2017\n}}\n\n'''Haminu Draman''' (born 1 April 1986)<ref>https://ghanasoccernet.com/player-profiles?player=620</ref> is a Ghanaian [[Association football|footballer]].\n\n==Club career==\nHaving started his career in Ghana with [[Heart of Lions F.C.]], Draman joined Serbian club [[Red Star Belgrade]] for the [[2005\u201306 First League of Serbia and Montenegro|2005\u201306]]. Having won the championship and the cup with Red Star moved to Turkey, where he made 31 league appearances for [[Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K.]] as they finished sixth in the Turkish [[Turkcell Super League|S\u00fcper Lig]].\n\nDraman signed a three-year contract with Russian Cup winners [[FC Lokomotiv Moscow|Lokomotiv Moscow]] on 19 June 2007. Draman joined Lokomotiv when the Russian transfer window opened on 1 August 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Draman's the man for Lokomotiv |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=552834.html |website=UEFA.com |accessdate=29 April 2020 |date=19 June 2007}}</ref> He was expected to replace Russian international [[Marat Izmailov]], who is on loan to Portuguese club [[Sporting Lisbon]] for a year.\n\nFollowing the transfer of Draman Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi's coach [[Ersun Yanal]] quit after just over a week in charge because he disagreed with the club's decision.<ref>{{cite news | date=9 June 2007 |url=http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=549284.html | title=Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi hit by Yanal U-turn | publisher=UEFA | accessdate=9 June 2007}}</ref> Yanal, who had previously been coach of Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi before leaving to become the [[Turkey national football team|Turkish national team]] coach, had signed a three-year contract with the club on 1 June 2007. \"The chairman's promises seem to have changed from the way they were before the agreement we made\" Yanal said. \"We would like to be a strong team but we sold Draman. The club want to try some players on trial in the meantime but this is not the way that I work.<ref>{{cite news | date=19 June 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/6768229.stm | title=Dramani moves to Russia | publisher=BBC | accessdate=19 June 2007}}</ref> Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi chairman Cavcav, who had been in charge of the club for 30 years, responded by saying: \"We met with the coach before and then I told him that I have to sell Draman to Locomotiv Moskva because all of the negotiations were over and I promised to sell him.<ref>{{cite news | date=11 June 2007 | url=http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php?enewsid=75496 | title=Coach departure induces fan protest at Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi | publisher=Turkish Daily News | accessdate=11 June 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930171102/http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php?enewsid=75496 | archivedate=30 September 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that English [[Premier League|Premiership]] side [[Stoke City]] were interested in signing Draman because of his speed and skills in the January 2008 transfer window, and that a fee of \u20ac3 million had been agreed.<ref>{{cite news | date=18 November 2008 | url=http://www.mtnfootball.com/live/content.php?Item_ID=17225 | title=Ghana's Draman Set For England | publisher=MTN Football | accessdate=18 November 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119032118/http://mtnfootball.com/live/content.php?Item_ID=17225 | archivedate=19 November 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February 2009, Draman signed for [[FC Kuban Krasnodar]] on loan from Lokomotiv Moscow.<ref>[http://english.sport-express.ru/news/13_3268/ Draman to Kuban] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719085619/http://english.sport-express.ru/news/13_3268/ |date=19 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 July 2011, Draman signed a one-year contract with French [[Ligue 2]] side [[AC Arles-Avignon]].<ref>{{cite news | date=12 July 2011 |url=http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-midfielder-haminu-dramani-joins-french-side-arles-avignon/ | title=Ghana midfielder Haminu Dramani joins French side Arles Avignon | publisher=GHANAsoccernet.com | accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Draman signed a two-year contract for Portuguese club [[Gil Vicente F.C.]] on a free transfer.<ref name=\"gil\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-winger-haminu-dramani-signs-two-deal-with-gil-vicente-on-a-free-transfer | title=Ghana winger Haminu Dramani signs two-deal with Gil Vicente on a free transfer | publisher = ghanasoccernet.com | accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref> This was after he had left Arles Avignon due to unpaid salary.<ref name=\"gil\"/>\n\nDraman left Gil Vicente during the winter-break, and by early 2014, he was back in Ghana, after almost a decade, by signing with [[Asante Kotoko S.C.]] His return turned out to be a great success as he won the double, the [[2013\u201314 Ghanaian Premier League]] and the 2014 [[Ghanaian FA Cup]] during his half-year spell with Asante Kotoko back in Ghana.<ref name=\"nft\">[http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/11613/Haminu_Draman.html Haminu Draman] at National-Football-Teams.com</ref>\n\nHe signed for [[FC Infonet]] in January 2016.<ref>[http://jalgpall.ee/fprotocol.php?st=style_fp.css&proto=1188&b=]</ref> With 3 goals in 23 appearances he helped them win their first ever national title, the [[2016 Meistriliiga]].<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n==International career==\nDraman was 19 when he made his international debut for Ghana in a friendly against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in [[Riyadh]] on 14 November 2005. He is a member of the [[Ghana national football team|national team]], and was called up to the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]. He scored his first goal of the tournament against the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S.]] on 22 June 2006.\n\nHe took a starring role in Ghana's International friendly against former World Champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] on 27 March 2007 where the Ghanaians lost 1\u20130, terrorising the Samba Boys right back [[Ilsinho]], before being dismissed late in the game for a second bookable offence on Ilsinho's replacement [[Daniel Alves]].\n\n====Note on name====\nThere was some confusion during the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] as Draman's surname was misspelled DRAMANI on the back of his shirt and, as a result, on [[FIFA]] documents. The Ghanaian FA confirm his name is Draman. He has also confirmed this himself in an interview to ''[[Sport Express]],'' a Russian newspaper.<ref>[http://www.sport-express.ru/newspaper/2007-07-04/1_2 \u0425\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0443 \u0414\u0420\u0410\u041c\u0410\u041d: \"\u041f\u041e\u041f\u0420\u041e\u0428\u0423 \u0423\u0411\u0420\u0410\u0422\u042c \u0411\u0423\u041a\u0412\u0423 \"\u0418\" \u0421 \u0424\u0423\u0422\u0411\u041e\u041b\u041a\u0418. \u042f \u2013 \u0414\u0420\u0410\u041c\u0410\u041d\"]</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===International===\n{{Updated|match played 11 August 2010}}<ref name=\"NFT Stats\">{{NFT|11613|name=Haminu Draman|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]]\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2005||1||0\n|-\n|2006||12||2\n|-\n|2007||4||0\n|-\n|2008||14||1\n|-\n|2009||7||1\n|-\n|2010||5||0\n|-\n!Total||43||4\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Ghana's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"NFT Stats\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!Goal!!Date!!Venue!!Opponent!!Score!!Result!!Competition!!Ref\n|-\n|1 ||22 June 2006||[[Frankenstadion]], [[Nuremberg]], Germany||{{fb|United States}}||<center>1\u20130</center>||<center>2\u20131</center>||[[2006 FIFA World Cup Group E]]||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana 2-1 USA|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=97410100/match=97410042/index.html#nosticky|website=fifa.com|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=7 July 2016|date=22 June 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|2 ||4 October 2006||[[International Stadium Yokohama|Nissan Stadium]], [[Yokohama]], Japan||{{fb|Japan}}||<center>1\u20130</center>||<center>1\u20130</center>||[[Exhibition game#Association football|Friendly]]||<ref>{{cite web|title=Japan 0-1 Ghana|url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/matches/report/13878/Japan_Ghana.html|website=national-football-teams.com|publisher=National Football Teams|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|3 ||9 February 2008||[[Baba Yara Stadium]], [[Kumasi]], Ghana||{{fb|Ivory Coast}}||<center>4\u20132</center>||<center>4\u20132</center>||Friendly||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana 4-2 Ivory Coast|url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/matches/report/1239/Ghana_Ivory_Coast.html|website=national-football-teams.com|publisher=National Football Teams|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|3 ||12 August 2009||[[Brisbane Road]], London, England||{{fb|Zambia}}||<center>4\u20131</center>||<center>4\u20131</center>||Friendly||<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana 4-1 Zambia|url=http://www.national-football-teams.com/matches/report/11869/Ghana_Zambia.html|website=national-football-teams.com|publisher=National Football Teams|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Red Star Belgrade'''\n*[[First League of Serbia and Montenegro]]: [[2005\u201306 First League of Serbia and Montenegro|2005\u201306]]<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n*[[Serbia and Montenegro Cup]]: [[2005\u201306 Serbia and Montenegro Cup|2006]]<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n'''Lokomotiv Moscow'''\n*[[Russian Cup (football)|Russian Cup]]: 2007<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n'''Asante Kotoko'''\n*[[Ghana Premier League]]: [[2013\u201314 Ghanaian Premier League|2013\u201314]]<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n*[[Ghanaian FA Cup]]: 2014<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n'''Infonet'''\n*[[Meistriliiga]]: [[2016 Meistriliiga|2016]]<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n===International===\n'''Ghana'''\n*[[Africa Cup of Nations]]: [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations|2010]] (runner-up)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/w/player/235367_DRAMAN_Haminu.html Fifa 2006 World Cup Profile]\n\n<br>\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Ghana squads\n| bg = White\n| fg = Black\n|list1=\n{{Ghana squad 2006 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Ghana squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Ghana squad 2008 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Ghana squad 2010 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Draman, Haminu}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2006 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2008 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2010 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:FC Lokomotiv Moscow players]]\n[[Category:Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K. footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:FC Kuban Krasnodar players]]\n[[Category:AC Arles-Avignon players]]\n[[Category:Gil Vicente F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Charlotte Independence players]]\n[[Category:Ghana international footballers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Red Star Belgrade footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:S\u00fcper Lig players]]\n[[Category:Russian Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 2 players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:USL Championship players]]\n[[Category:Heart of Lions F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Asante Kotoko SC players]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Russia]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:FCI Tallinn players]]\n[[Category:Meistriliiga players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Estonia]]\n[[Category:Serbian SuperLiga players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ghanaian footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Haminu Draman\n| image          = Haminu.JPG\n| image_size      = 300px\n| caption        = Haminu Draman playing for [[FC Kuban Krasnodar|Kuban]]\n| fullname       = Haminu Draman\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1986|4|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Techiman]], Ghana\n| height         = {{convert|1.73|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| position       = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = \n| clubnumber     = \n| youthyears1    =           |youthclubs1 =\n| years1         = 2004\u20132005 |clubs1  = [[Heart of Lions]]                       |caps1  = 3   |goals1  = 0\n| years2         = 2005\u20132006 |clubs2  = [[Red Star Belgrade]]                    |caps2  = 4   |goals2  = 1\n| years3         = 2006\u20132007 |clubs3  = [[Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K.|Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi]]   |caps3  = 31  |goals3  = 2\n| years4         = 2007\u20132011 |clubs4  = [[FC Lokomotiv Moscow|Lokomotiv Moscow]] |caps4  = 8   |goals4  = 0\n| years5         = 2009      |clubs5  = \u2192 [[FC Kuban Krasnodar|Kuban]] (loan)    |caps5  = 27  |goals5  = 3\n| years6         = 2011\u20132013 |clubs6  = [[AC Arles-Avignon|Arles-Avignon]]       |caps6  = 30  |goals6  = 2\n| years7         = 2013\u20132014 |clubs7  = [[Gil Vicente F.C.|Gil Vicente]]         |caps7  = 3   |goals7  = 0\n| years8         = 2014      |clubs8  = [[Asante Kotoko SC|Asante Kotoko]]       |caps8  =     |goals8  =\n| years9         = 2015      |clubs9  = [[Charlotte Independence]]               |caps9  = 2   |goals9  = 0\n| years10        = 2016      |clubs10 = [[FC Infonet|Infonet]]                   |caps10 = 23  |goals10 = 3\n| nationalyears1 = 2005\u20132010 |nationalteam1 = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] |nationalcaps1 = 43 |nationalgoals1 = 4\n| pcupdate       = 13 June 2017\n| ntupdate       = 13 June 2017\n}}\n\n'''Haminu Draman''' (born 1 April 1986)<ref>https://ghanasoccernet.com/player-profiles?player=620</ref> is a Ghanaian [[Association football|footballer]].\n\n==Club career==\nHaving started his career in Ghana with [[Heart of Lions F.C.]], Draman joined Serbian club [[Red Star Belgrade]] for the [[2005\u201306 First League of Serbia and Montenegro|2005\u201306]]. Having won the championship and the cup with Red Star moved to Turkey, where he made 31 league appearances for [[Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi S.K.]] as they finished sixth in the Turkish [[Turkcell Super League|S\u00fcper Lig]].\n\nDraman signed a three-year contract with Russian Cup winners [[FC Lokomotiv Moscow|Lokomotiv Moscow]] on 19 June 2007. Draman joined Lokomotiv when the Russian transfer window opened on 1 August 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Draman's the man for Lokomotiv |url=https://www.uefa.com/insideuefa/news/newsid=552834.html |website=UEFA.com |accessdate=29 April 2020 |date=19 June 2007}}</ref> He was expected to replace Russian international [[Marat Izmailov]], who is on loan to Portuguese club [[Sporting Lisbon]] for a year.\n\nFollowing the transfer of Draman Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi's coach [[Ersun Yanal]] quit after just over a week in charge because he disagreed with the club's decision.<ref>{{cite news | date=9 June 2007 |url=http://www.uefa.com/footballeurope/news/kind=2/newsid=549284.html | title=Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi hit by Yanal U-turn | publisher=UEFA | accessdate=9 June 2007}}</ref> Yanal, who had previously been coach of Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi before leaving to become the [[Turkey national football team|Turkish national team]] coach, had signed a three-year contract with the club on 1 June 2007. \"The chairman's promises seem to have changed from the way they were before the agreement we made\" Yanal said. \"We would like to be a strong team but we sold Draman. The club want to try some players on trial in the meantime but this is not the way that I work.<ref>{{cite news | date=19 June 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/africa/6768229.stm | title=Dramani moves to Russia | publisher=BBC | accessdate=19 June 2007}}</ref> Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi chairman Cavcav, who had been in charge of the club for 30 years, responded by saying: \"We met with the coach before and then I told him that I have to sell Draman to Locomotiv Moskva because all of the negotiations were over and I promised to sell him.<ref>{{cite news | date=11 June 2007 | url=http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php?enewsid=75496 | title=Coach departure induces fan protest at Gen\u00e7lerbirli\u011fi | publisher=Turkish Daily News | accessdate=11 June 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930171102/http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php?enewsid=75496 | archivedate=30 September 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIt was reported that English [[Premier League|Premiership]] side [[Stoke City]] were interested in signing Draman because of his speed and skills in the January 2008 transfer window, and that a fee of \u20ac3 million had been agreed.<ref>{{cite news | date=18 November 2008 | url=http://www.mtnfootball.com/live/content.php?Item_ID=17225 | title=Ghana's Draman Set For England | publisher=MTN Football | accessdate=18 November 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119032118/http://mtnfootball.com/live/content.php?Item_ID=17225 | archivedate=19 November 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 February 2009, Draman signed for [[FC Kuban Krasnodar]] on loan from Lokomotiv Moscow.<ref>[http://english.sport-express.ru/news/13_3268/ Draman to Kuban] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719085619/http://english.sport-express.ru/news/13_3268/ |date=19 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 July 2011, Draman signed a one-year contract with French [[Ligue 2]] side [[AC Arles-Avignon]].<ref>{{cite news | date=12 July 2011 |url=http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-midfielder-haminu-dramani-joins-french-side-arles-avignon/ | title=Ghana midfielder Haminu Dramani joins French side Arles Avignon | publisher=GHANAsoccernet.com | accessdate=12 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Draman signed a two-year contract for Portuguese club [[Gil Vicente F.C.]] on a free transfer.<ref name=\"gil\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-winger-haminu-dramani-signs-two-deal-with-gil-vicente-on-a-free-transfer | title=Ghana winger Haminu Dramani signs two-deal with Gil Vicente on a free transfer | publisher = ghanasoccernet.com | accessdate=1 August 2013}}</ref> This was after he had left Arles Avignon due to unpaid salary.<ref name=\"gil\"/>\n\nDraman left Gil Vicente during the winter-break, and by early 2014, he was back in Ghana, after almost a decade, by signing with [[Asante Kotoko S.C.]] His return turned out to be a great success as he won the double, the [[2013\u201314 Ghanaian Premier League]] and the 2014 [[Ghanaian FA Cup]] during his half-year spell with Asante Kotoko back in Ghana.<ref name=\"nft\">[http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/11613/Haminu_Draman.html Haminu Draman] at National-Football-Teams.com</ref>\n\nHe signed for [[FC Infonet]] in January 2016.<ref>[http://jalgpall.ee/fprotocol.php?st=style_fp.css&proto=1188&b=]</ref> With 3 goals in 23 appearances he helped them win their first ever national title, the [[2016 Meistriliiga]].<ref name=\"nft\"/>\n\n==International career==\nDraman was 19 when he made his international debut for Ghana in a friendly against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]] in [[Riyadh]] on 14 November 2005. He is a member of the [[Ghana national football team|national team]], and was called up to the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]. He scored his first goal of the tournament against the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S.]] on 22 June 2006.\n\nHe took a starring role in Ghana's International friendly against former World Champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] on 27 March 2007 where the Ghanaians lost 1\u20130, terrorising the Samba Boys right back [[Ilsinho]], before being dismissed late in the game for a second bookable offence on Ilsinho's replacement [[Daniel Alves]].\n\n====Note on name====\nThere was some confusion during the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] as Draman's surname was misspelled DRAMANI on the back of his shirt and, as a result, on [[FIFA]] documents. The Ghanaian FA confirm his name is Draman. He has also confirmed this himself in an interview to ''[[Sport Express]],'' a Russian newspaper.<ref>[http://www.sport-express.ru/newspaper/2007-07-04/1_2 \u0425\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0443 \u0414\u0420\u0410\u041c\u0410\u041d: \"\u041f\u041e\u041f\u0420\u041e\u0428\u0423 \u0423\u0411\u0420\u0410\u0422\u042c \u0411\u0423\u041a\u0412\u0423 \"\u0418\" \u0421 \u0424\u0423\u0422\u0411\u041e\u041b\u041a\u0418. \u042f \u2013 \u0414\u0420\u0410\u041c\u0410\u041d\"]</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===International===\n{{Updated|match played 11 August 2010}}<ref name=\"NFT Stats\">{{NFT|11613|name=Haminu Draman|accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"8\"|[[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]]\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2005||1||0\n|-\n|2006||12||2\n|-\n|2007||4||0\n|-\n|2008||14||1\n|-\n|2009||7||1\n|-\n|2010||5||0\n|-\n!Total||43||4\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n:''Scores and results list Ghana's goal tally first.''<ref name=\"NFT Stats\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ International goals by date, venue, cap, opponent, score, result and competition\n|-\n!Goal!!Date!!Venue!!Opponent!!Score!!Result!!Competition!!Ref\n|-\n|1 ||22 June 2006||[[Frankenstadion]], [[Nuremberg]], [[Germany]]||{{fb|United States}}||<center>1\u20130</center>||<center>2\u20131</center>||[[2006 FIFA World Cup Group E]]||<ref>{{cite w