{"title_page": "1,2-Dibromoethylene", "text_new": "{{Chembox\n<!-- Images -->\n| ImageFileL1 = (Z)-1,2-Dibromoethene.png\n| ImageCaptionL2 = (''Z'')-1,2-Dibromoethylene\n| ImageFileR1 = (E)-1,2-Dibromoethene.png\n| ImageCaptionR2 = (''E'')-1,2-Dibromoethylene\n| ImageFileL2 =Cis1,2-Dibromoethylene.png\n| ImageFileR2 = Trans1,2-Dibromoethylene.png\n| ImageSizeR2 = \n| ImageAlt1 =\n<!-- Names -->\n| IUPACName = 1,2-Dibromoethene\n| OtherNames =\n<!-- Sections -->\n| Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo1 = 590-12-5\n| CASNo1_Comment = (''Z'')\n| ChemSpiderID = 558875\n| ChemSpiderID_Comment = (''Z'')\n| CASNo2 = 590-11-4\n| CASNo2_Comment = (''E'')\n| ChemSpiderID1 = 553502\n| ChemSpiderID1_Comment = (''E'')\n| PubChem1 = 643776\n| PubChem1_Comment = (''Z'')\n| PubChem2 = 637929\n| PubChem2_Comment = (''E'')\n| EC_number = 208-747-6\n| UNII1 = 0S4D0712FY\n| UNII2 = 64UWX7EBVO\n| StdInChI=1S/C2H2Br2/c3-1-2-4/h1-2H/b2-1+\n| StdInChIKey = UWTUEMKLYAGTNQ-OWOJBTEDSA-N\n| SMILES = C(=CBr)Br \n  }}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| C=2 | H=2 | Br=2 \n| Appearance = colorless liquid\n| Density = 2.246 g/cm{{sup|3}} \n| BoilingPtC = 110\n| Solubility = \n  }}\n| Section3 = {{Chembox Hazards\n| GHSPictograms = {{GHS05}}{{GHS06}}{{GHS07}}\n| GHSSignalWord = Danger\n| HPhrases = {{H-phrases|301|314|315|319|335}}\n| PPhrases = {{P-phrases|260|261|264|270|271|280|301+310|301+330+331|302+352|303+361+353|304+340|305+351+338|310|312|321|330|332+313|337+313|362|363|403+233|405|501}}\n| MainHazards = Toxic\n| FlashPt =\n| AutoignitionPt =\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''1,2-Dibromoethylene''', also known as '''1,2-dibromoethene''' and '''acetylene dibromide''', is a dihalogenated unsaturated compound with one [[bromine]] on each of the two [[carbon]] atoms. There are two [[isomer]]s of this compound, [[Cis\u2013trans isomerism|''cis'' and ''trans'']]. Both isomers are colorless liquids.\n\n==Synthesis==\n(''E'')-1,2-Dibromoethene can be synthesized by [[halogenation]] of [[acetylene]] with bromine Br{{sub|2}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mhhe.com/physsci/chemistry/carey/student/olc/ch09additionreactionsofalkynes.html |title=Chapter 9: Addition Reactions of Alkynes |website=Organic Chemistry 4e Carey |publisher=McGraw-Hill |access-date=9 June 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412094457/http://www.mhhe.com/physsci/chemistry/carey/student/olc/ch09additionreactionsofalkynes.html |archive-date=April 12, 2016}}</ref> In order to prevent the formation tetrahalogenated compounds, acetylene is used in excess, with Br{{sub|2}} as the [[limiting reagent]].\n:[[Image:Halogenation of Alynes (1).jpg|Halogenation of Alynes (1).jpg]]\nAlternately, halogenation of this kind could also be achieved through the use of two equivalents of [[N-bromosuccinimide|''N''-bromosuccinimide]] and [[lithium bromide]] (LiBr). ''N''-Bromosuccinimide provides Br{{sup|+}} as an [[electrophile]], which is followed by Br{{sup|\u2212}} from LiBr.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.thieme-connect.de/products/ejournals/pdf/10.1055/s-2006-941558.pdf |title=N-Bromosuccinimide and Lithium Bromide: An Efficient Combination for the Dibromination of Carbon\u2013Carbon Unsaturated Bonds |journal=[[Synlett]] |volume=2006 |issue=8 |pages=1269\u20131271 | doi=10.1055/s-2006-941558 |last1=Shao |first1=L.-X. |last2=Shi |first2=M. |year=2006}}</ref>\n\n:[[Image:HalogenationLiBrNBS.png|400px]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dibromoethylene, 1, 2-}}\n[[Category:Organobromides]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chembox\n<!-- Images -->\n| ImageFileL1 = (Z)-1,2-Dibromoethene.png\n| ImageCaptionL2 = (''Z'')-1,2-Dibromoethylene\n| ImageFileR1 = (E)-1,2-Dibromoethene.png\n| ImageCaptionR2 = (''E'')-1,2-Dibromoethylene\n| ImageFileL2 =Cis1,2-Dibromoethylene.png\n| ImageFileR2 = Trans1,2-Dibromoethylene.png\n| ImageSizeR2 = \n| ImageAlt1 =\n<!-- Names -->\n| IUPACName = 1,2-Dibromoethene\n| OtherNames =\n<!-- Sections -->\n| Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| CASNo1 = 590-12-5\n| CASNo1_Comment = (''Z'')\n| ChemSpiderID = 558875\n| ChemSpiderID_Comment = (''Z'')\n| CASNo2 = 590-11-4\n| CASNo2_Comment = (''E'')\n| ChemSpiderID1 = 553502\n| ChemSpiderID1_Comment = (''E'')\n| PubChem1 = 643776\n| PubChem1_Comment = (''Z'')\n| PubChem2 = 637929\n| PubChem2_Comment = (''E'')\n| EC_number = 208-747-6\n| UNII1 = 0S4D0712FY\n| UNII2 = 64UWX7EBVO\n| StdInChI=1S/C2H2Br2/c3-1-2-4/h1-2H/b2-1+\n| StdInChIKey = UWTUEMKLYAGTNQ-OWOJBTEDSA-N\n| SMILES = C(=CBr)Br \n  }}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| C=2 | H=2 | Br=2 \n| Appearance = colorless liquid\n| Density = 2.246 g/cm{{sup|3}} \n| BoilingPtC = 110\n| Solubility = \n  }}\n| Section3 = {{Chembox Hazards\n| GHSPictograms = {{GHS05}}{{GHS06}}{{GHS07}}\n| GHSSignalWord = Danger\n| HPhrases = {{H-phrases|301|314|315|319|335}}\n| PPhrases = {{P-phrases|260|261|264|270|271|280|301+310|301+330+331|302+352|303+361+353|304+340|305+351+338|310|312|321|330|332+313|337+313|362|363|403+233|405|501}}\n| MainHazards = Toxic\n| FlashPt =\n| AutoignitionPt =\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''1,2-Dibromoethylene''', also known as '''1,2-dibromoethene''' and '''acetylene dibromide''', is a dihalogenated unsaturated compound with one [[bromine]] on each of the two [[carbon]] atoms. There are two [[isomer]]s of this compound, [[Cis\u2013trans isomerism|''cis'' and ''trans'']]. Both isomers are colorless liquids.\n\n==Synthesis==\n(''E'')-1,2-Dibromoethene can be synthesized by [[halogenation]] of [[acetylene]] with bromine Br{{sub|2}}.<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.mhhe.com/physsci/chemistry/carey/student/olc/ch09additionreactionsofalkynes.html | title = Chapter 9: Alkynes | journal =  |volume= |issue= |pages=| doi=| pmid= | pmc= | last1 =  | first1 =  | last2 =  | first2 = |access-date=9 June 2017}}</ref> In order to prevent the formation tetrahalogenated compounds, acetylene is used in excess, with Br{{sub|2}} as the [[limiting reagent]].\n:[[Image:Halogenation of Alynes (1).jpg|Halogenation of Alynes (1).jpg]]\nAlternately, halogenation of this kind could also be achieved through the use of two equivalents of [[N-bromosuccinimide|''N''-bromosuccinimide]] and [[lithium bromide]] (LiBr). ''N''-Bromosuccinimide provides Br{{sup|+}} as an [[electrophile]], which is followed by Br{{sup|\u2212}} from LiBr.<ref>{{cite journal | url = https://www.thieme-connect.de/products/ejournals/pdf/10.1055/s-2006-941558.pdf | title = N-Bromosuccinimide and Lithium Bromide: An Efficient Combination for the Dibromination of Carbon\u2013Carbon Unsaturated Bonds | journal = Synlett |volume= 2006|issue= 8|pages=1269\u20131271| doi=10.1055/s-2006-941558 | pmid= | pmc= | last1 = Shao | first1 = L | last2 = Shi | first2 = M | year = 2006 }}</ref>\n\n:[[Image:HalogenationLiBrNBS.png|400px]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dibromoethylene, 1, 2-}}\n[[Category:Organobromides]]\n", "name_user": "Dawkeye", "label": "safe", "comment": "fmt/update references", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1,2-Dibromoethylene"}
{"title_page": "Hand clasping", "text_new": "[[File:William J. Clinton - NCI Visuals Online.jpg|thumb|220px|'''''L''''' [[phenotype]] of hand clasping<br>([[Bill Clinton]])]]\n'''Hand clasping''' is the superposition of each [[finger]] of one [[hand]] over the corresponding finger of the opposite hand. When clasping the hands, a person tends to interlace the fingers in one of two ways. People who hold the fingers of the right hand above the left fingers are classified as [[phenotype]] ''R'' (right), while those who hold the fingers of the left hand above those of the right are phenotype ''L'' (left).\n\nAlthough some people do not exhibit a preference for one type of hand clasping, most do. Once adopted, the method of hand clasping tends to be consistent throughout life. When an individual attempts to clasp the hands in the opposite configuration from the usual one, that person may feel a sense that something is out of the ordinary.\n\nIt was noted that the ''R'' type occurs more frequently in women than in men, which led to popular speculation that all persons with ''L'' phenotype are more emotional than persons with ''R'' type.{{Dubious|date=February 2016}}<ref>Ferronato S., Thomas D., Sadava D. (1974): Preferences for handedness, arm folding, and hand clasping in families. Hum. Hered., 24: 345-351,[PubMed: 4461659, related citations]</ref>\n\nLai and Walsh (1965) suspect that [[genotype|genetic factors]] are important in determining these characteristics. They looked at a sample of 18 families.<ref>Lai L. Y. C., Walsh R. J. (1965): The patterns of hand clasping in different ethnic groups. Hum. Biol. 37: 312-319.[PubMed: 5836191, related citations]</ref>\n\nBased on the comparison of a series of monozygotic and dizygotic [[twins]], Freire-Maia (1961) concluded that the preference in the type of hand clasping was affected by certain genetic factors, and (perhaps) to a significant extent.<ref>Freire-Maia A. (1961): Twin data on hand clasping: a reanalysis. Acta Genet. Statist. Med. 10: 207-211.</ref>\n\nFalk and Ayala (1971) found a significant correlation between parent-offspring and for this feature suggested model polygenic inheritance.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Falk | first1 = C. T. | last2 = Ayala | first2 = F. J. | year = 1971 | title = Genetic aspects of arm folding and hand clasping. Jpn | url = | journal = J. Hum. Genet | volume = 15 | issue = | pages = 241\u2013247 }}</ref>\n\nMartin (1975) presented the results of studies of [[twins]] and found that genetic factors are still determining the phenotypic expression of this trait.<ref>Martin N. G (1975): No evidence for a genetic basis of tongue rolling or hand clasping. J. Hered., 66: 179-180. [PubMed: 1236879, related citations] [Full Text: HighWire Press].</ref>\n\nReiss (1999) found that 55% of the [[population]] belongs to the phenotype ''L'', and 44% have a \"right type\" clasping; the remaining 1% did not care.<ref>Pons J. (1961): Hand clasping  ''Ann. Hum. Genet'' 25: 141-144. PMID 14487797 </ref><ref>Reiss M. (1999): The genetics of hand-clasping-a review and a familial study. ''Ann. Hum. Biol.'', 26: 39-48. PMID 9974082</ref>\n\nIn support of the hypothesis about the significant influence of genetic factors on the [[phenotype|phenotypic expression]] of the extreme [[Polymorphism (biology)|dimorphism]] clearly demarcated by the data on a very wide range of variation in the frequency of phenotypes tested parts of the world's population.{{confusing-inline|date=July 2019}}\n\n==''R'' phenotype distribution==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"toccolours\" 0.5em solid #999; 100%\n|- \n|  style=\"background:#dfd; \"|'''Population'''\n|  style=\"background:#f3fff3; \"|'''N''' \n|'''R''' (%)\n|style=\"background:#f3fff3; \"|References\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Belgium]] \n|644      \n|48.1     \n|Leguebe (1967)<ref>Leguebe  1967  hand clasping:  \u00e9tude anthropologique et g\u00e9n\u00e9tique. Bull. Soc. Roy. Antrop. Pr\u00e9hist., 78: 81-107.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#dfd;\" | [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]  \n|10,073    \n|55.1   \n|Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1979)<ref>Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R., Berberovi\u0107 Lj., Sofrad\u017eija A. (1979): Distribucija fenotipova na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i prekr\u0161tanja ruku u stanovni\u0161tvu Bosne i Hercegovine. God.Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu, 32: 101-116.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Bulgaria]]  \n|?   \n|70.1 \n| Boev, Todorov (1970)<ref>Boev, Todorov, 1970,  in: Gavrilovi\u0107 \u017d., Bo\u017ei\u0107 V. (1972): Prou\u010davanje na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i pekr\u0161tanja ruku kod stanovni\u0161tva u Vojvodini. Genetika, 4 (1): 59-61.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Greece]]  \n|?        \n|81.2    \n|Pelecanos (1969)<ref>Pelecanos 1969,  in:   Py\u017cuk M. (1976):  Hand clasping, and arm- and leg-folding in Polish rural  population. Acta F. R. N. Univ Come., Anthropologia, 23: 219-223.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Poland]]   \n|771  \n| 48.0   \n| Wolanski et al. (1973)<ref>Wolanski et al 1973, in:  Py\u017cuk M. (1976):  Hand clasping, and arm- and leg-folding in Polish rural  population. Acta F. R. N. Univ Come., Anthropologia, 23: 219-223.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Scotland]]     \n|598  \n|60.0\n| Lutz (1908)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Lutz | first1 = F. E. | year = 1908 | title = The inheritance of the manner of clasping the hands | url = | journal = Am. Nat. | volume = 42 | issue = | pages = 195\u2013196 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Serbia]]: [[U\u017eice]]  \n|2,217    \n|54.0   \n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al.(1979)<ref>Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R., Berberovi\u0107 Lj., Sofrad\u017eija A. (1979): Distribucija fenotipova na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i prekr\u0161tanja ruku u stanovni\u0161tvu Bosne i Hercegovine. God.Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu, 32: 101-116.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Serbia]]:  [[Voivodina]]   \n|2,686      \n|51.9  \n|Gavrilovi\u0107, Bo\u017ei\u0107 (1972)<ref>Gavrilovi\u0107 \u017d., Bo\u017ei\u0107 V. (1972): Prou\u010davanje na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i pekr\u0161tanja ruku kod stanovni\u0161tva u Vojvodini. Genetika, 4 (1): 59-61.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Spain]]     \n|486    \n|52.1     \n|Pons (1961)<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pons | first1 = J | year = 1961 | title = Hand clasping (Spanish data) | url = | journal = Ann. Hum. Genet. | volume = 25 | issue = | pages = 141\u2013144 }}</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Sweden]]    \n|981    \n|52.1    \n|Beckman,  Elston (1962)<ref>Beckman L.  Elston R. 1962 Data  on bilateral variations in man: handedness, hand clasping and arm folding in Swedes. ''Hum. Biol.'', 34: 99-103.</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arm folding]]\n*[[Hand]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/inheritance/observable/ (en)\n\n[[Category:Hand gestures]]\n[[Category:Classical genetics]]\n[[Category:Human population genetics]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:William J. Clinton - NCI Visuals Online.jpg|thumb|220px|'''''L''''' [[phenotype]] of hand clasping<br>([[Bill Clinton]])]]\n'''Hand clasping''' is the superposition of each [[finger]] of one [[hand]] over the corresponding finger of the opposite hand. When clasping the hands, a person tends to interlace the fingers in one of two ways. People who hold the fingers of the right hand above the left fingers are classified as [[phenotype]] ''R'' (right), while those who hold the fingers of the left hand above those of the right are phenotype ''L'' (left).\n\nAlthough some people do not exhibit a preference for one type of hand clasping, most do. Once adopted, the method of hand clasping tends to be consistent throughout life. When an individual attempts to clasp the hands in the opposite configuration from the usual one, that person may feel a sense that something is out of the ordinary.\n\nIt was noted that the ''R'' type occurs more frequently in women than in men, which led to popular speculation that all persons with ''L'' phenotype are more emotional than persons with ''R'' type.{{Dubious|date=February 2016}}<ref>Ferronato S., Thomas D., Sadava D. (1974): Preferences for handedness, arm folding, and hand clasping in families. Hum. Hered., 24: 345-351,[PubMed: 4461659, related citations]</ref>\n\nLai and Walsh (1965) suspect that [[genotype|genetic factors]] are important in determining these characteristics. They looked at a sample of 18 families.<ref>Lai L. Y. C., Walsh R. J. (1965): The patterns of hand clasping in different ethnic groups. Hum. Biol. 37: 312-319.[PubMed: 5836191, related citations]</ref>\n\nBased on the comparison of a series of monozygotic and dizygotic [[twins]], Freire-Maia (1961) concluded that the preference in the type of hand clasping was affected by certain genetic factors, and (perhaps) to a significant extent.<ref>Freire-Maia A. (1961): Twin data on hand clasping: a reanalysis. Acta Genet. Statist. Med. 10: 207-211.</ref>\n\nFalk and Ayala (1971) found a significant correlation between parent-offspring and for this feature suggested model polygenic inheritance.<ref>Falk C. T., Ayala F. J. (1971): Genetic aspects of arm folding and hand clasping. Jpn. J. Hum. Genet. 15: 241-247.</ref>\n\nMartin (1975) presented the results of studies of [[twins]] and found that genetic factors are still determining the phenotypic expression of this trait.<ref>Martin N. G (1975): No evidence for a genetic basis of tongue rolling or hand clasping. J. Hered., 66: 179-180. [PubMed: 1236879, related citations] [Full Text: HighWire Press].</ref>\n\nReiss (1999) found that 55% of the [[population]] belongs to the phenotype ''L'', and 44% have a \"right type\" clasping; the remaining 1% did not care.<ref>Pons J. (1961): Hand clasping . Ann. Hum. Genet., 25: 141-144. [PubMed: 14487797, related citations]</ref><ref>Reiss M. (1999): The genetics of hand-clasping-a review and a familial study. Ann. Hum. Biol., 26: 39-48. [PubMed: 9974082, related citations].</ref>\n\nIn support of the hypothesis about the significant influence of genetic factors on the [[phenotype|phenotypic expression]] of the extreme [[Polymorphism (biology)|dimorphism]] clearly demarcated by the data on a very wide range of variation in the frequency of phenotypes tested parts of the world's population.{{confusing-inline|date=July 2019}}\n\n==''R'' phenotype distribution==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" class=\"toccolours\" 0.5em solid #999; 100%\n|- \n|  style=\"background:#dfd; \"|'''Population'''\n|  style=\"background:#f3fff3; \"|'''N''' \n|'''R''' (%)\n|style=\"background:#f3fff3; \"|References\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Belgium]] \n|644      \n|48.1     \n|Leguebe (1967)<ref>Leguebe  1967  hand clasping:  \u00e9tude anthropologique et g\u00e9n\u00e9tique. Bull. Soc. Roy. Antrop. Pr\u00e9hist., 78: 81-107.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#dfd;\" | [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]  \n|10,073    \n|55.1   \n|Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al. (1979)<ref>Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R., Berberovi\u0107 Lj., Sofrad\u017eija A. (1979): Distribucija fenotipova na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i prekr\u0161tanja ruku u stanovni\u0161tvu Bosne i Hercegovine. God.Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu, 32: 101-116.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Bulgaria]]  \n|?   \n|70.1 \n| Boev, Todorov (1970)<ref>Boev, Todorov, 1970,  in: Gavrilovi\u0107 \u017d., Bo\u017ei\u0107 V. (1972): Prou\u010davanje na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i pekr\u0161tanja ruku kod stanovni\u0161tva u Vojvodini. Genetika, 4 (1): 59-61.</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Greece]]  \n|?        \n|81.2    \n|Pelecanos (1969)<ref>Pelecanos 1969,  in:   Py\u017cuk M. (1976):  Hand clasping, and arm- and leg-folding in Polish rural  population. Acta F. R. N. Univ Come., Anthropologia, 23: 219-223.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Poland]]   \n|771  \n| 48.0   \n| Wolanski et al. (1973)<ref>Wolanski et al 1973, in:  Py\u017cuk M. (1976):  Hand clasping, and arm- and leg-folding in Polish rural  population. Acta F. R. N. Univ Come., Anthropologia, 23: 219-223.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Scotland]]     \n|598  \n|60.0\n| Lutz (1908)<ref>Lutz F. E. (1908): The inheritance of the manner of clasping the hands. Am. Nat., 42:  195-196.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Serbia]]: [[U\u017eice]]  \n|2,217    \n|54.0   \n| Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 et al.(1979)<ref>Had\u017eiselimovi\u0107 R., Berberovi\u0107 Lj., Sofrad\u017eija A. (1979): Distribucija fenotipova na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i prekr\u0161tanja ruku u stanovni\u0161tvu Bosne i Hercegovine. God.Biol. inst. Univ. u Sarajevu, 32: 101-116.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Serbia]]:  [[Voivodina]]   \n|2,686      \n|51.9  \n|Gavrilovi\u0107, Bo\u017ei\u0107 (1972)<ref>Gavrilovi\u0107 \u017d., Bo\u017ei\u0107 V. (1972): Prou\u010davanje na\u010dina sklapanja \u0161aka i pekr\u0161tanja ruku kod stanovni\u0161tva u Vojvodini. Genetika, 4 (1): 59-61.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#ddffdd;fff3;''|[[Spain]]     \n|486    \n|52.1     \n|Pons (1961)<ref>Pons J. (1961): Hand clasping  (Spanish data).  Ann. Hum. Genet., 25: 141-144.</ref>\n|-\n|style=\"background:#dfd;\"|[[Sweden]]    \n|981    \n|52.1    \n|Beckman,  Elston (1962)<ref>Beckman L.  Elston R. 1962 Data  on bilateral variations in man: handedness, hand clasping and arm folding in Swedes. Hum. Biol., 34: 99-103.</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Arm folding]]\n*[[Hand]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/inheritance/observable/ (en)\n\n[[Category:Hand gestures]]\n[[Category:Classical genetics]]\n[[Category:Human population genetics]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated 3 journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/